insert into platform_topic_master (subject_slug, topic_slug, page_name, sections)
values
('additional-maths', '1-1-notation-functions-and-indices', '1.1 Notation, Functions and Indices', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "What do the words constant, coefficient, term and variable mean?", "html": "<p>Algebra has a precise vocabulary. Using it correctly is a real exam skill — mark schemes and command words are written in it.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>A <strong>variable</strong> (or <strong>unknown</strong>) is a letter standing for a quantity, e.g. \\( x \\). We call it a <em>variable</em> when its value may change, and an <em>unknown</em> when we are solving to find its one value.</li>\n              <li>A <strong>constant</strong> is a fixed number, e.g. the \\( 7 \\) in \\( 3x + 7 \\).</li>\n              <li>A <strong>term</strong> is a single part of an expression separated by \\( + \\) or \\( - \\): \\( 3x^2 \\), \\( -5x \\) and \\( 7 \\) are the three terms of \\( 3x^2 - 5x + 7 \\).</li>\n              <li>A <strong>coefficient</strong> is the number multiplying a variable. In \\( -5x \\) the coefficient is \\( -5 \\) (the sign belongs to it).</li>\n              <li>An <strong>expression</strong> is a collection of terms with no equals sign, e.g. \\( 3x^2 - 5x + 7 \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>An expression has no equals sign; the moment you write \\( = \\) you have an <strong>equation</strong> (next card).</p>", "check": {"question": "In the expression \\( 4 - 6x^2 \\), what is the coefficient of \\( x^2 \\)?", "options": ["\\( 4 \\)", "\\( 2 \\)", "\\( -6 \\)", "\\( 6 \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The coefficient is the number multiplying \\( x^2 \\), including its sign: \\( -6 \\). The \\( 4 \\) is a constant and \\( 2 \\) is the index."}}, {"title": "What is the difference between an equation and an identity?", "html": "<p>Both use an equals-type sign, but they mean different things.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>An <strong>equation</strong> is true only for particular value(s) of the variable. \\( 2x + 1 = 7 \\) is true <em>only</em> when \\( x = 3 \\); you <em>solve</em> it.</li>\n              <li>An <strong>identity</strong> is true for <em>every</em> value of the variable. We use the sign \\( \\equiv \\) to signal this: \\[ (x + 1)^2 \\equiv x^2 + 2x + 1. \\] Whatever number you put in for \\( x \\), both sides are equal.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Index laws (later cards) are identities: \\( a^m \\times a^n \\equiv a^{m+n} \\) holds for all valid \\( a, m, n \\). You will meet \\( \\equiv \\) when a question asks you to prove or \"show that\" two expressions are the same.</p>", "check": {"question": "Which statement is an identity (true for all values of \\( x \\))?", "options": ["\\( 3x = 12 \\)", "\\( x^2 = 9 \\)", "\\( 2(x + 3) \\equiv 2x + 6 \\)", "\\( x + 1 = 0 \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "\\( 2(x+3) \\) expands to \\( 2x+6 \\) for every \\( x \\), so it is an identity. The others are true only for particular values of \\( x \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you use function notation f(x)?", "html": "<p><strong>Function notation</strong> \\( \\text{f}(x) \\) names a rule: it reads \"f of \\( x \\)\" and tells you what to do to the input \\( x \\). To <strong>evaluate</strong> \\( \\text{f}(3) \\), substitute \\( 3 \\) for every \\( x \\).</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — given \\( \\text{f}(x) = 2x^2 - 5x + 1 \\), find \\( \\text{f}(3) \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Replace every \\( x \\) with \\( 3 \\): \\( \\text{f}(3) = 2(3)^2 - 5(3) + 1 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Powers first: \\( (3)^2 = 9 \\), so \\( 2 \\times 9 = 18 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Then \\( -5 \\times 3 = -15 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Add up: \\( 18 - 15 + 1 = 4 \\), so \\[ \\text{f}(3) = 4. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Watch negatives: \\( \\text{f}(-2) = 2(-2)^2 - 5(-2) + 1 = 8 + 10 + 1 = 19 \\). A squared negative is positive, and subtracting a negative adds.</p>", "check": {"question": "If \\( \\text{f}(x) = x^2 + 2 \\), what is \\( \\text{f}(-3) \\)?", "options": ["\\( 11 \\)", "\\( -7 \\)", "\\( -3 \\)", "\\( -9 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\text{f}(-3) = (-3)^2 + 2 = 9 + 2 = 11 \\). A negative squared is positive, so it is \\( +9 \\), not \\( -9 \\)."}}, {"title": "What are the three main index laws?", "html": "<p>An <strong>index</strong> (or <strong>power</strong>) tells you how many times to multiply the <strong>base</strong> by itself: \\( a^4 = a \\times a \\times a \\times a \\). Three laws let you combine powers of the <em>same base</em>.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td><strong>Multiplying</strong> — <em>add</em> the indices: \\[ a^m \\times a^n = a^{m+n}. \\] e.g. \\( 2^3 \\times 2^4 = 2^{7} = 128 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><strong>Dividing</strong> — <em>subtract</em> the indices: \\[ a^m \\div a^n = a^{m-n}. \\] e.g. \\( x^7 \\div x^2 = x^{5} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td><strong>Power of a power</strong> — <em>multiply</em> the indices: \\[ (a^m)^n = a^{mn}. \\] e.g. \\( (y^3)^4 = y^{12} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><strong>Careful:</strong> the laws only work for the <em>same base</em>. \\( 2^3 \\times 5^2 \\) does <strong>not</strong> simplify by adding indices. When a coefficient is involved, deal with it separately: \\( (2x^3)^2 = 2^2 \\times x^{3 \\times 2} = 4x^6 \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( a^5 \\times a^3 \\).", "options": ["\\( a^{15} \\)", "\\( a^8 \\)", "\\( a^2 \\)", "\\( 2a^8 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Multiplying powers of the same base means you ADD the indices: \\( a^{5+3} = a^8 \\). Multiplying the indices (\\( a^{15} \\)) is the classic error."}}, {"title": "What do a zero index and a negative index mean?", "html": "<p>These two rules follow directly from the division law.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Zero index:</strong> \\( a^m \\div a^m = a^{0} \\), but anything divided by itself is \\( 1 \\), so \\[ a^0 = 1 \\quad (a \\neq 0). \\] Every non-zero base to the power zero is \\( 1 \\) — not \\( 0 \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Negative index:</strong> a minus sign in the index means \"take the <strong>reciprocal</strong>\": \\[ a^{-n} = \\frac{1}{a^{n}}. \\] It does <em>not</em> make the answer negative.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — evaluate \\( 2^{-3} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. The negative index means take the reciprocal: \\( 2^{-3} = \\dfrac{1}{2^{3}} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Work out the positive power: \\( 2^3 = 8 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. So \\[ 2^{-3} = \\frac{1}{8}. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The answer \\( \\tfrac{1}{8} \\) is positive — a negative index never means a negative number.</p>", "check": {"question": "Evaluate \\( 5^{-2} \\).", "options": ["\\( -25 \\)", "\\( -10 \\)", "\\( \\frac{1}{25} \\)", "\\( \\frac{1}{10} \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "\\( 5^{-2} = \\dfrac{1}{5^2} = \\dfrac{1}{25} \\). The negative index takes the reciprocal; the result stays positive."}}, {"title": "How do you evaluate a fractional index like 8^(2/3)?", "html": "<p>A fractional index combines a root and a power.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>The <strong>denominator is a root</strong>: \\( a^{1/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a} \\). So \\( a^{1/2} = \\sqrt{a} \\) and \\( a^{1/3} = \\sqrt[3]{a} \\).</li>\n              <li>The <strong>numerator is a power</strong>: \\[ a^{m/n} = \\left(\\sqrt[n]{a}\\right)^{m} = \\sqrt[n]{a^{m}}. \\]</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Take the root <em>first</em> — the numbers stay small and it is easier by hand.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — evaluate \\( 8^{2/3} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Denominator \\( 3 \\) is the root: \\( \\sqrt[3]{8} = 2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Numerator \\( 2 \\) is the power: \\( 2^{2} = 4 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. So \\[ 8^{2/3} = \\left(\\sqrt[3]{8}\\right)^{2} = 2^{2} = 4. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Combine with a negative index too: \\( 16^{-1/2} = \\dfrac{1}{16^{1/2}} = \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{16}} = \\dfrac{1}{4} \\). The minus flips it, the half roots it.</p>", "check": {"question": "Evaluate \\( 27^{2/3} \\).", "options": ["\\( 9 \\)", "\\( 18 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)", "\\( 729 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\sqrt[3]{27} = 3 \\), then \\( 3^2 = 9 \\). Root first, then power."}}, {"title": "Which formulae must you memorise here?", "html": "<p>The <strong>index laws are MEMORISE material</strong> — they are <em>not</em> on the exam formula sheet. Learn all seven as identities you can recall instantly:</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>\\( a^m \\times a^n = a^{m+n} \\)</td><td>\\( a^m \\div a^n = a^{m-n} \\)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>\\( (a^m)^n = a^{mn} \\)</td><td>\\( a^0 = 1 \\)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>\\( a^{-n} = \\dfrac{1}{a^{n}} \\)</td><td>\\( a^{1/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a} \\)</td></tr>\n              <tr><td colspan=\"2\">\\( a^{m/n} = \\left(\\sqrt[n]{a}\\right)^{m} \\)</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Function notation and the vocabulary (constant, coefficient, identity \\( \\equiv \\), variable) also carry no formula-sheet support — they are assumed knowledge used throughout the whole paper. This first lesson is the toolkit every later topic relies on, so fluency here pays off everywhere.</p>", "check": {"question": "Which of these is TRUE for every non-zero base \\( a \\)?", "options": ["\\( a^0 = 0 \\)", "\\( a^0 = 1 \\)", "\\( a^0 = a \\)", "\\( a^0 = -1 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Any non-zero number raised to the power \\( 0 \\) equals \\( 1 \\); this follows from \\( a^m \\div a^m = a^0 = 1 \\)."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Variable", "definition": "A letter standing for a quantity whose value may change, e.g. \\( x \\)."}, {"term": "Unknown", "definition": "The letter whose single value you solve an equation to find."}, {"term": "Constant", "definition": "A fixed number with no variable attached, e.g. the \\( 7 \\) in \\( 3x+7 \\)."}, {"term": "Coefficient", "definition": "The number multiplying a variable, including its sign, e.g. \\( -5 \\) in \\( -5x \\)."}, {"term": "Term", "definition": "A single part of an expression separated by \\( + \\) or \\( - \\)."}, {"term": "Expression", "definition": "A collection of terms with no equals sign, e.g. \\( 3x^2 - 5x + 7 \\)."}, {"term": "Equation", "definition": "A statement with \\( = \\) that is true only for particular value(s) of the variable."}, {"term": "Identity \\( \\equiv \\)", "definition": "A statement true for every value of the variable, e.g. \\( (x+1)^2 \\equiv x^2+2x+1 \\)."}, {"term": "Index (power)", "definition": "How many times the base is multiplied by itself: \\( a^4 = a \\times a \\times a \\times a \\)."}, {"term": "Function notation \\( \\text{f}(x) \\)", "definition": "A named rule; evaluate \\( \\text{f}(3) \\) by substituting \\( 3 \\) for every \\( x \\)."}, {"term": "Multiplication law", "definition": "\\( a^m \\times a^n = a^{m+n} \\) — same base, add indices."}, {"term": "Division law", "definition": "\\( a^m \\div a^n = a^{m-n} \\) — same base, subtract indices."}, {"term": "Power of a power", "definition": "\\( (a^m)^n = a^{mn} \\) — multiply the indices."}, {"term": "Zero index", "definition": "\\( a^0 = 1 \\) for any non-zero base \\( a \\)."}, {"term": "Negative index", "definition": "\\( a^{-n} = \\frac{1}{a^{n}} \\) — take the reciprocal, stays positive."}, {"term": "Unit fractional index", "definition": "\\( a^{1/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a} \\) — the denominator is the root."}, {"term": "General fractional index", "definition": "\\( a^{m/n} = \\left(\\sqrt[n]{a}\\right)^{m} \\) — root then power."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Simplify \\( a^6 \\times a^4 \\).", "options": ["\\( a^{24} \\)", "\\( a^{10} \\)", "\\( a^{2} \\)", "\\( 2a^{10} \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Multiplying powers of the same base ADDS the indices: \\( a^{6+4} = a^{10} \\). Multiplying them (\\( a^{24} \\)) is the classic slip."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( x^9 \\div x^4 \\).", "options": ["\\( x^{13} \\)", "\\( x^{2.25} \\)", "\\( x^{5} \\)", "\\( x^{36} \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Dividing powers of the same base SUBTRACTS the indices: \\( x^{9-4} = x^{5} \\)."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( (y^3)^5 \\).", "options": ["\\( y^{8} \\)", "\\( y^{15} \\)", "\\( y^{2} \\)", "\\( y^{35} \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Power of a power MULTIPLIES the indices: \\( y^{3 \\times 5} = y^{15} \\). Adding them (\\( y^8 \\)) confuses this law with the multiplication law."}, {"question": "Evaluate \\( 7^0 \\).", "options": ["\\( 0 \\)", "\\( 1 \\)", "\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 70 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Any non-zero base to the power \\( 0 \\) equals \\( 1 \\), so \\( 7^0 = 1 \\), never \\( 0 \\)."}, {"question": "Evaluate \\( 2^{-4} \\).", "options": ["\\( -16 \\)", "\\( -8 \\)", "\\( \\frac{1}{16} \\)", "\\( \\frac{1}{8} \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "\\( 2^{-4} = \\dfrac{1}{2^4} = \\dfrac{1}{16} \\). The negative index takes the reciprocal; it does not make the value negative."}, {"question": "Evaluate \\( 16^{1/2} \\).", "options": ["\\( 8 \\)", "\\( 4 \\)", "\\( 32 \\)", "\\( 256 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A \\( \\tfrac{1}{2} \\) index means the square root: \\( 16^{1/2} = \\sqrt{16} = 4 \\)."}, {"question": "Evaluate \\( 8^{2/3} \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{16}{3} \\)", "\\( 4 \\)", "\\( 16 \\)", "\\( 32 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( 8^{2/3} = \\left(\\sqrt[3]{8}\\right)^2 = 2^2 = 4 \\). Multiplying \\( 8 \\times \\tfrac{2}{3} = \\tfrac{16}{3} \\) treats the index as a multiplier — a common error."}, {"question": "Evaluate \\( 25^{-1/2} \\).", "options": ["\\( -5 \\)", "\\( \\frac{1}{5} \\)", "\\( 5 \\)", "\\( -\\frac{1}{5} \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The half roots it and the minus reciprocates it: \\( 25^{-1/2} = \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{25}} = \\dfrac{1}{5} \\), which is positive."}, {"question": "In the expression \\( 9 - 4x^3 \\), what is the coefficient of \\( x^3 \\)?", "options": ["\\( -4 \\)", "\\( 4 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)", "\\( 9 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The coefficient is the number multiplying \\( x^3 \\), including its sign: \\( -4 \\). The \\( 3 \\) is the index and \\( 9 \\) is a constant."}, {"question": "Given \\( \\text{f}(x) = 3x - 4 \\), find \\( \\text{f}(2) \\).", "options": ["\\( 2 \\)", "\\( 10 \\)", "\\( 6 \\)", "\\( 1 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Substitute \\( x = 2 \\): \\( 3(2) - 4 = 6 - 4 = 2 \\)."}, {"question": "Given \\( \\text{f}(x) = x^2 - 4x \\), find \\( \\text{f}(-1) \\).", "options": ["\\( -3 \\)", "\\( 5 \\)", "\\( -5 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( \\text{f}(-1) = (-1)^2 - 4(-1) = 1 + 4 = 5 \\). The square is positive and subtracting \\( -4(-1) \\) adds \\( 4 \\)."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( (2x^2)^3 \\).", "options": ["\\( 2x^6 \\)", "\\( 6x^6 \\)", "\\( 8x^5 \\)", "\\( 8x^6 \\)"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Cube both parts: \\( 2^3 = 8 \\) and \\( (x^2)^3 = x^{6} \\), giving \\( 8x^6 \\). Forgetting to cube the \\( 2 \\) gives \\( 2x^6 \\)."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "To simplify \\( a^m \\times a^n \\) you [add] the indices, and to simplify \\( a^m \\div a^n \\) you [subtract] them."}, {"text": "The rule \\( (a^m)^n \\) tells you to [multiply] the two indices together."}, {"text": "For any non-zero base, \\( a^0 \\) equals [1]."}, {"text": "A negative index means take the [reciprocal], so \\( a^{-n} \\) becomes a fraction."}, {"text": "In the term \\( 4x^3 \\), the number \\( 4 \\) is the [coefficient] and the number \\( 3 \\) is the [index]."}, {"text": "The symbol \\( \\equiv \\) means the statement is an [identity], which is true for [all] values of the variable."}, {"text": "In \\( a^{1/n} \\) the fraction \\( \\frac{1}{n} \\) tells you to take the [nth] root of \\( a \\)."}, {"text": "In an equation you solve to find the value of the [unknown], whereas in an expression there is no equals sign to [solve]."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "\\( a^m \\times a^n = a^{m+n} \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "Multiplying powers of the same base adds the indices — this is the first index law."}, {"statement": "\\( a^0 = 0 \\) for every base \\( a \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "Any non-zero base to the power \\( 0 \\) equals \\( 1 \\), not \\( 0 \\): \\( a^0 = 1 \\)."}, {"statement": "\\( (a^m)^n = a^{m+n} \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "Power of a power MULTIPLIES the indices: \\( (a^m)^n = a^{mn} \\). Adding them confuses this with the multiplication law."}, {"statement": "\\( a^{-n} = \\frac{1}{a^{n}} \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "A negative index means take the reciprocal; the result is a fraction, not a negative number."}, {"statement": "\\( a^{1/2} = \\sqrt{a} \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "An index of \\( \\tfrac{1}{2} \\) is the square root; more generally \\( a^{1/n} = \\sqrt[n]{a} \\)."}, {"statement": "In \\( 5x^3 \\) the coefficient is \\( 3 \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "The coefficient is the number multiplying the variable, so it is \\( 5 \\). The \\( 3 \\) is the index (power)."}, {"statement": "An identity (written with \\( \\equiv \\)) is true for every value of the variable.", "answer": true, "explain": "That is exactly what \\( \\equiv \\) signals, e.g. \\( (x+1)^2 \\equiv x^2 + 2x + 1 \\) holds for all \\( x \\)."}, {"statement": "\\( 8^{2/3} = \\frac{16}{3} \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "\\( 8^{2/3} = \\left(\\sqrt[3]{8}\\right)^2 = 2^2 = 4 \\). Multiplying \\( 8 \\times \\tfrac{2}{3} \\) treats the index as a multiplier — wrong."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "\\( a^0 = 0 \\)", "truth": "Any non-zero base to the power zero is \\( 1 \\). A weak answer copies the \\( 0 \\); a strong answer recalls \\( a^m \\div a^m = a^0 = 1 \\).", "check": {"question": "Evaluate \\( 12^0 \\).", "options": ["\\( 1 \\)", "\\( 0 \\)", "\\( 12 \\)", "\\( 120 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Every non-zero base to the power \\( 0 \\) is \\( 1 \\), so \\( 12^0 = 1 \\)."}}, {"myth": "\\( a^m \\times a^n = a^{mn} \\) (multiply the indices)", "truth": "Multiplying powers of the same base ADDS the indices. A weak answer multiplies; a strong answer writes \\( a^m \\times a^n = a^{m+n} \\), keeping the power-of-a-power rule separate.", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( x^2 \\times x^5 \\).", "options": ["\\( x^{7} \\)", "\\( x^{10} \\)", "\\( x^{3} \\)", "\\( x^{25} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Add the indices: \\( x^{2+5} = x^7 \\). \\( x^{10} \\) comes from wrongly multiplying them."}}, {"myth": "\\( (a^m)^n = a^{m+n} \\) (add the indices)", "truth": "Power of a power MULTIPLIES the indices. A weak answer adds; a strong answer writes \\( (a^m)^n = a^{mn} \\).", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( (x^4)^2 \\).", "options": ["\\( x^{8} \\)", "\\( x^{6} \\)", "\\( x^{2} \\)", "\\( x^{16} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Multiply the indices: \\( x^{4 \\times 2} = x^8 \\). Adding them gives the wrong \\( x^6 \\)."}}, {"myth": "\\( 2^{-3} = -8 \\) (a negative index gives a negative answer)", "truth": "A negative index means the reciprocal, not a negative value. A weak answer negates; a strong answer writes \\( 2^{-3} = \\dfrac{1}{2^3} = \\dfrac{1}{8} \\).", "check": {"question": "Evaluate \\( 3^{-2} \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{1}{9} \\)", "\\( -9 \\)", "\\( -6 \\)", "\\( 9 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 3^{-2} = \\dfrac{1}{3^2} = \\dfrac{1}{9} \\); the answer is positive."}}, {"myth": "\\( 8^{2/3} = 8 \\times \\frac{2}{3} = \\frac{16}{3} \\)", "truth": "A fractional index is a root and a power, not a multiplier. A weak answer multiplies the base by the fraction; a strong answer takes the root first: \\( \\left(\\sqrt[3]{8}\\right)^2 = 2^2 = 4 \\).", "check": {"question": "Evaluate \\( 4^{3/2} \\).", "options": ["\\( 8 \\)", "\\( 6 \\)", "\\( \\frac{3}{2} \\)", "\\( 64 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\sqrt{4} = 2 \\), then \\( 2^3 = 8 \\). Root first, then power."}}, {"myth": "In \\( 6x^2 \\) the coefficient is \\( 2 \\)", "truth": "The coefficient is the number multiplying the variable, so it is \\( 6 \\). A weak answer names the index; a strong answer distinguishes coefficient (\\( 6 \\)) from index (\\( 2 \\)).", "check": {"question": "What is the coefficient of \\( x \\) in \\( -7x \\)?", "options": ["\\( -7 \\)", "\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 1 \\)", "\\( x \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The coefficient includes its sign, so it is \\( -7 \\)."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Read the command word: Simplify vs Evaluate", "html": "<p><strong>Simplify</strong> means combine into one power/term but leave letters in: \\( a^5 \\times a^3 \\to a^8 \\). <strong>Evaluate</strong> (or \"work out\") means give a single number: \\( 8^{2/3} \\to 4 \\). <strong>Write down / state</strong> means no working is expected — just the answer. Giving a decimal when a simplified power was asked for, or an unfinished power when a number was asked for, both lose marks.</p>", "check": {"question": "\"Evaluate \\( 16^{1/2} \\)\" is asking you to:", "options": ["Give a single number", "Leave it as a power", "Draw a graph", "Round to 3 s.f. only"], "answer": 0, "explain": "''Evaluate'' wants a numerical value: \\( \\sqrt{16} = 4 \\)."}}, {"title": "Show your working on fractional indices", "html": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> \\( 27^{2/3} = 18 \\) (multiplied \\( 27 \\times \\tfrac{2}{3} \\)) — a wrong single number with no method shown. <strong>Partial:</strong> writes \\( \\sqrt[3]{27} = 3 \\) then stops. <strong>Full marks:</strong> \\( \\sqrt[3]{27} = 3 \\), then \\( 3^2 = 9 \\). Show the root step and the power step so a slip costs one mark, not all of them.</p>", "check": {"question": "Why write out both the root step and the power step?", "options": ["To earn method marks even if the final value slips", "It wastes time", "To use more paper", "It is never needed"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Splitting a fractional index into its root and power shows method, protecting the marks if one step slips."}}, {"title": "Index laws are MEMORISE, not on the sheet", "html": "<p>The index laws are <strong>not</strong> printed on the exam formula sheet — you must recall them. A frequent slip is applying a law across <em>different</em> bases: \\( 2^3 \\times 5^2 \\) cannot be combined by adding indices because the bases differ. Only same-base powers combine.</p>", "check": {"question": "Which product can be simplified by adding indices?", "options": ["\\( 3^4 \\times 3^2 \\)", "\\( 3^4 \\times 5^2 \\)", "\\( 2^4 \\times 7^4 \\)", "\\( 3^4 + 3^2 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Only \\( 3^4 \\times 3^2 \\) shares a base, giving \\( 3^6 \\). Different bases cannot be combined this way."}}]}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths', '1-2-surds-and-algebraic-fractions', '1.2 Surds and Algebraic Fractions', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "How do you simplify a surd?", "html": "<p>A <strong>surd</strong> is a root that cannot be written as an exact rational number, such as \\( \\sqrt{3} \\) or \\( \\sqrt{12} \\). You <strong>simplify</strong> a surd by taking out the largest <strong>perfect-square factor</strong>.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>Use the rule \\( \\sqrt{ab} = \\sqrt{a}\\,\\sqrt{b} \\), choosing \\( a \\) to be the biggest square that divides the number.</li>\n              <li>A surd is in simplest form when the number left under the root has <strong>no square factor</strong> bigger than 1.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — simplify \\( \\sqrt{12} \\) and \\( \\sqrt{125} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( 12 = 4 \\times 3 \\), and \\( 4 \\) is the largest square factor.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( \\sqrt{12} = \\sqrt{4}\\,\\sqrt{3} = 2\\sqrt{3} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( 125 = 25 \\times 5 \\), and \\( 25 \\) is a square factor.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. \\( \\sqrt{125} = \\sqrt{25}\\,\\sqrt{5} = 5\\sqrt{5} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Always look for the <em>largest</em> square factor — using \\( \\sqrt{12} = \\sqrt{2}\\,\\sqrt{6} \\) does not finish the job.</p>", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( \\sqrt{200} \\).", "options": ["\\( 10\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 2\\sqrt{50} \\)", "\\( 100\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 20\\sqrt{2} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 200 = 100 \\times 2 \\), so \\( \\sqrt{200} = \\sqrt{100}\\,\\sqrt{2} = 10\\sqrt{2} \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you add, subtract and multiply surds?", "html": "<p>You can only add or subtract <strong>like surds</strong> — surds with the same number under the root. Simplify first so the like surds appear.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( \\sqrt{12} + \\sqrt{27} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( \\sqrt{12} = 2\\sqrt{3} \\) and \\( \\sqrt{27} = \\sqrt{9}\\,\\sqrt{3} = 3\\sqrt{3} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Both are multiples of \\( \\sqrt{3} \\): \\( 2\\sqrt{3} + 3\\sqrt{3} = 5\\sqrt{3} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>To <strong>multiply</strong> surds use \\( \\sqrt{a}\\,\\sqrt{b} = \\sqrt{ab} \\); for example \\( \\sqrt{3}\\times\\sqrt{12} = \\sqrt{36} = 6 \\). To <strong>expand brackets</strong>, multiply out as usual and collect like surds.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — expand \\( (3 + \\sqrt{2})^2 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( (3+\\sqrt{2})^2 = (3+\\sqrt{2})(3+\\sqrt{2}) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( = 9 + 3\\sqrt{2} + 3\\sqrt{2} + \\sqrt{2}\\,\\sqrt{2} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( \\sqrt{2}\\,\\sqrt{2} = 2 \\), so \\( = 9 + 6\\sqrt{2} + 2 = 11 + 6\\sqrt{2} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><strong>Never</strong> write \\( \\sqrt{a} + \\sqrt{b} = \\sqrt{a+b} \\): that is false (\\( \\sqrt{9}+\\sqrt{16} = 7 \\), not \\( \\sqrt{25} = 5 \\)).</p>", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( \\sqrt{50} - \\sqrt{8} \\).", "options": ["\\( 3\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{42} \\)", "\\( 2\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 42\\sqrt{2} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\sqrt{50} = 5\\sqrt{2} \\) and \\( \\sqrt{8} = 2\\sqrt{2} \\), so \\( 5\\sqrt{2} - 2\\sqrt{2} = 3\\sqrt{2} \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you rationalise a denominator?", "html": "<p><strong>Rationalising</strong> means clearing the surd out of the denominator. The trick is to multiply the fraction by a clever form of 1.</p>\n            <p><strong>Simple case</strong> — for \\( \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\), multiply top and bottom by \\( \\sqrt{3} \\):</p>\n            <p>\\[ \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\times \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}} = \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{3}. \\]</p>\n            <p><strong>Conjugate case</strong> — for \\( \\frac{1}{2+\\sqrt{3}} \\), multiply by the <strong>conjugate</strong> \\( 2-\\sqrt{3} \\). The conjugate flips only the sign of the surd, and \\( (a+\\sqrt{b})(a-\\sqrt{b}) = a^2 - b \\) is a whole number (difference of two squares).</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( \\dfrac{1}{2+\\sqrt{3}} \\times \\dfrac{2-\\sqrt{3}}{2-\\sqrt{3}} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Denominator: \\( (2+\\sqrt{3})(2-\\sqrt{3}) = 4 - 3 = 1 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. So \\( \\dfrac{2-\\sqrt{3}}{1} = 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Watch the denominator: it is \\( a^2 - b \\), <em>not</em> \\( a^2 + b \\). For \\( 5 - \\sqrt{2} \\) the conjugate product is \\( 25 - 2 = 23 \\), not 27.</p>", "check": {"question": "Rationalise \\( \\frac{1}{3-\\sqrt{2}} \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{3+\\sqrt{2}}{7} \\)", "\\( \\frac{3-\\sqrt{2}}{7} \\)", "\\( \\frac{3+\\sqrt{2}}{11} \\)", "\\( 3+\\sqrt{2} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Multiply by the conjugate \\( 3+\\sqrt{2} \\): denominator \\( 9 - 2 = 7 \\), giving \\( \\frac{3+\\sqrt{2}}{7} \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you simplify an algebraic fraction?", "html": "<p>Simplify an algebraic fraction the same way as a numerical one: <strong>factorise</strong> the numerator and denominator, then <strong>cancel common factors</strong>.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>You may only cancel <strong>factors</strong> (things multiplied), never individual <strong>terms</strong> (things added).</li>\n              <li>Common tools: the difference of two squares \\( a^2 - b^2 = (a+b)(a-b) \\), and factorising quadratics.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — simplify \\( \\dfrac{x^2 + 5x + 6}{x^2 - 4} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Factorise the top: \\( x^2 + 5x + 6 = (x+2)(x+3) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Factorise the bottom: \\( x^2 - 4 = (x+2)(x-2) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Cancel the common factor \\( (x+2) \\): \\( \\dfrac{(x+2)(x+3)}{(x+2)(x-2)} = \\dfrac{x+3}{x-2} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>You cannot cancel the \\( x \\)''s or the numbers separately — only the whole bracket \\( (x+2) \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 9}{x + 3} \\).", "options": ["\\( x - 3 \\)", "\\( x + 3 \\)", "\\( x - 9 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x^2 - 9 = (x+3)(x-3) \\); cancel \\( (x+3) \\) to leave \\( x - 3 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you add and subtract algebraic fractions?", "html": "<p>Put both fractions over a <strong>common denominator</strong>, combine the numerators, then simplify. The common denominator is usually the two denominators multiplied together.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( \\dfrac{1}{x-1} - \\dfrac{2}{x+1} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Common denominator \\( (x-1)(x+1) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Rewrite: \\( \\dfrac{(x+1) - 2(x-1)}{(x-1)(x+1)} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Expand the numerator: \\( x + 1 - 2x + 2 \\) (the minus multiplies <em>both</em> terms of \\( -2(x-1) \\)).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Collect: \\( \\dfrac{3 - x}{(x-1)(x+1)} \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The biggest trap is the <strong>minus sign</strong>: \\( -2(x-1) = -2x + 2 \\), not \\( -2x - 2 \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( \\dfrac{3}{x+2} + \\dfrac{1}{x-1} \\).", "options": ["\\( \\dfrac{4x-1}{(x+2)(x-1)} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{4x+1}{(x+2)(x-1)} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{4}{(x+2)(x-1)} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{3x-1}{(x+2)(x-1)} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 3(x-1) + (x+2) = 3x - 3 + x + 2 = 4x - 1 \\), over \\( (x+2)(x-1) \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you multiply and divide algebraic fractions?", "html": "<p>To <strong>multiply</strong>: factorise everything, cancel any common factor top-to-bottom, then multiply the numerators and the denominators.</p>\n            <p>To <strong>divide</strong>: multiply by the <strong>reciprocal</strong> of the second fraction (flip it), then proceed as for multiplication.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 1}{x + 2} \\div \\dfrac{x - 1}{x + 2} \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Flip the divisor: \\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 1}{x + 2} \\times \\dfrac{x + 2}{x - 1} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Factorise: \\( x^2 - 1 = (x+1)(x-1) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Cancel \\( (x+2) \\) and \\( (x-1) \\): \\( \\dfrac{(x+1)(x-1)(x+2)}{(x+2)(x-1)} = x + 1 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Never flip the first fraction — only the one you are <em>dividing by</em>.</p>", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 1}{x + 2} \\div \\dfrac{x - 1}{x + 2} \\).", "options": ["\\( x + 1 \\)", "\\( x - 1 \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{x+1}{x+2} \\)", "\\( x^2 - 1 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Multiply by the reciprocal, factorise \\( x^2-1=(x+1)(x-1) \\), and cancel to get \\( x + 1 \\)."}}, {"title": "What do ''exact'' and ''detailed reasoning'' require?", "html": "<p>Surd questions almost always carry a command word that controls how you must answer.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>''Exact''</strong> means leave the answer in surd or fraction form — \\( \\frac{15+\\sqrt{2}}{23} \\), not \\( 0.696 \\). A decimal-only answer scores no marks.</li>\n              <li><strong>''In this question you must show detailed reasoning'' (DR)</strong> means the full method must be written out. A correct answer taken straight from a calculator scores <strong>zero</strong>, even when it is right.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>For a rationalising DR question (like 2023 Q4(b)) you must <em>show</em> the unsimplified numerator over the common denominator before you tidy it up — that visible step is a mark in its own right.</p>", "check": {"question": "On a ''detailed reasoning'' surd question, what scores 0 marks?", "options": ["A correct answer with no working (straight from a calculator)", "Showing every algebraic step", "Leaving the answer as a surd", "Writing the common denominator first"], "answer": 0, "explain": "DR requires the full analytical method; an unexplained calculator answer earns nothing even if correct."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Surd", "definition": "A root that is not an exact rational number, e.g. \\( \\sqrt{3} \\)."}, {"term": "Simplifying a surd", "definition": "Take out the largest perfect-square factor: \\( \\sqrt{12} = 2\\sqrt{3} \\)."}, {"term": "Like surds", "definition": "Surds with the same root, e.g. \\( 2\\sqrt{3} \\) and \\( 5\\sqrt{3} \\); only these add or subtract."}, {"term": "\\( \\sqrt{a}\\,\\sqrt{b} \\)", "definition": "Equals \\( \\sqrt{ab} \\); e.g. \\( \\sqrt{3}\\,\\sqrt{12} = \\sqrt{36} = 6 \\)."}, {"term": "Rationalising the denominator", "definition": "Removing a surd from the denominator of a fraction."}, {"term": "Conjugate of \\( a + \\sqrt{b} \\)", "definition": "The expression \\( a - \\sqrt{b} \\) (only the surd''s sign changes)."}, {"term": "\\( (a+\\sqrt{b})(a-\\sqrt{b}) \\)", "definition": "Equals \\( a^2 - b \\), a whole number (difference of two squares)."}, {"term": "Rationalise \\( \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{a}} \\)", "definition": "Multiply top and bottom by \\( \\sqrt{a} \\) to get \\( \\frac{\\sqrt{a}}{a} \\)."}, {"term": "Algebraic fraction", "definition": "A fraction whose numerator and/or denominator are polynomials."}, {"term": "Simplifying algebraic fractions", "definition": "Factorise the top and bottom, then cancel common factors."}, {"term": "Cancelling rule", "definition": "You may cancel factors (multiplied), never terms (added)."}, {"term": "Adding algebraic fractions", "definition": "Use a common denominator, then combine the numerators."}, {"term": "Dividing algebraic fractions", "definition": "Multiply by the reciprocal of the divisor (flip the second fraction)."}, {"term": "Difference of two squares", "definition": "\\( a^2 - b^2 = (a+b)(a-b) \\); the key to conjugates and factorising."}, {"term": "''Exact''", "definition": "Leave surds/fractions, never a decimal, e.g. \\( \\frac{15+\\sqrt{2}}{23} \\)."}, {"term": "''Detailed reasoning'' (DR)", "definition": "Full method shown; a calculator-only answer scores 0."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Simplify \\( \\sqrt{12} \\).", "options": ["\\( 2\\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( 6\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 3\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 4\\sqrt{3} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 12 = 4 \\times 3 \\), so \\( \\sqrt{12} = 2\\sqrt{3} \\). \\( 6\\sqrt{2} \\) is \\( \\sqrt{72} \\); \\( 4\\sqrt{3} \\) is \\( \\sqrt{48} \\)."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( \\sqrt{125} \\).", "options": ["\\( 5\\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( 25\\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( 5\\sqrt{25} \\)", "\\( 5 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 125 = 25 \\times 5 \\), so \\( \\sqrt{125} = \\sqrt{25}\\,\\sqrt{5} = 5\\sqrt{5} \\)."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( \\sqrt{8} + \\sqrt{18} \\).", "options": ["\\( 5\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{26} \\)", "\\( 5\\sqrt{26} \\)", "\\( 6\\sqrt{2} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\sqrt{8} = 2\\sqrt{2} \\), \\( \\sqrt{18} = 3\\sqrt{2} \\); like surds add to \\( 5\\sqrt{2} \\). You cannot add the numbers under the root to get \\( \\sqrt{26} \\)."}, {"question": "Expand and simplify \\( (2 + \\sqrt{3})(2 - \\sqrt{3}) \\).", "options": ["\\( 1 \\)", "\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 4 - \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( 4 + 2\\sqrt{3} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Difference of two squares: \\( 2^2 - (\\sqrt{3})^2 = 4 - 3 = 1 \\). This is why a conjugate rationalises a denominator."}, {"question": "Expand and simplify \\( (3 + \\sqrt{2})^2 \\).", "options": ["\\( 11 + 6\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 11 \\)", "\\( 9 + 2\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 11 + 3\\sqrt{2} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( (3+\\sqrt{2})^2 = 9 + 6\\sqrt{2} + 2 = 11 + 6\\sqrt{2} \\); do not forget the middle term \\( 2 \\times 3 \\times \\sqrt{2} \\)."}, {"question": "Rationalise \\( \\dfrac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\).", "options": ["\\( \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{1}{3} \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{3}{\\sqrt{3}} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Multiply top and bottom by \\( \\sqrt{3} \\): \\( \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}\\,\\sqrt{3}} = \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{3} \\)."}, {"question": "Rationalise \\( \\dfrac{6}{\\sqrt{2}} \\).", "options": ["\\( 3\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 6\\sqrt{2} \\)", "\\( 3 \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{3} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\dfrac{6}{\\sqrt{2}} \\times \\dfrac{\\sqrt{2}}{\\sqrt{2}} = \\dfrac{6\\sqrt{2}}{2} = 3\\sqrt{2} \\)."}, {"question": "To rationalise \\( \\dfrac{1}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\) you multiply top and bottom by:", "options": ["\\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( 2 + \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{1}{2 - \\sqrt{3}} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The conjugate \\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\) makes the denominator \\( 4 - 3 = 1 \\), clearing the surd."}, {"question": "Rationalise \\( \\dfrac{1}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\) fully.", "options": ["\\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{2 - \\sqrt{3}}{7} \\)", "\\( 2 + \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{2 - \\sqrt{3}}{5} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Denominator \\( (2+\\sqrt{3})(2-\\sqrt{3}) = 4 - 3 = 1 \\), so the answer is \\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\). Using \\( 4 + 3 = 7 \\) is the classic sign error."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 9}{x + 3} \\).", "options": ["\\( x - 3 \\)", "\\( x + 3 \\)", "\\( x - 9 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Factorise \\( x^2 - 9 = (x+3)(x-3) \\) then cancel \\( (x+3) \\) to get \\( x - 3 \\). You cannot cancel the \\( 9 \\) on its own."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( \\dfrac{x^2 + 5x + 6}{x^2 - 4} \\).", "options": ["\\( \\dfrac{x+3}{x-2} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{x+3}{x+2} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{5x+6}{-4} \\)", "\\( x + 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\dfrac{(x+2)(x+3)}{(x+2)(x-2)} \\); cancel \\( (x+2) \\) to get \\( \\dfrac{x+3}{x-2} \\)."}, {"question": "Simplify \\( \\dfrac{1}{x-1} - \\dfrac{2}{x+1} \\).", "options": ["\\( \\dfrac{3 - x}{(x-1)(x+1)} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{-x - 1}{(x-1)(x+1)} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{3 - x}{x-1} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{-1}{(x-1)(x+1)} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Numerator \\( (x+1) - 2(x-1) = x + 1 - 2x + 2 = 3 - x \\). The option \\( -x-1 \\) comes from writing \\( -2(x-1) = -2x - 2 \\) — a sign error."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "To simplify a surd, take out the largest perfect [square] factor."}, {"text": "In \\( \\sqrt{12} = 2\\sqrt{3} \\) we used the fact that \\( 12 = 4 \\times 3 \\) and \\( \\sqrt{4} = \\) [2]."}, {"text": "You can only add or subtract surds when they are [like] surds (the same number under the root)."}, {"text": "To rationalise \\( \\frac{1}{2+\\sqrt{3}} \\) you multiply by its [conjugate], which is \\( 2-\\sqrt{3} \\)."}, {"text": "Multiplying \\( (2+\\sqrt{3})(2-\\sqrt{3}) \\) gives the whole number [1]."}, {"text": "To simplify an algebraic fraction you first [factorise] the top and bottom, then cancel common factors."}, {"text": "To add \\( \\frac{1}{x-1} \\) and \\( \\frac{2}{x+1} \\) you write them over the common denominator [(x-1)(x+1)]."}, {"text": "The instruction ''show detailed reasoning'' means a [calculator] answer with no working scores zero."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "\\( \\sqrt{50} = 5\\sqrt{2} \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "\\( 50 = 25 \\times 2 \\), so \\( \\sqrt{50} = \\sqrt{25}\\,\\sqrt{2} = 5\\sqrt{2} \\). ✓"}, {"statement": "\\( \\sqrt{12} + \\sqrt{3} = \\sqrt{15} \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "You cannot add the numbers under the root. \\( \\sqrt{12} = 2\\sqrt{3} \\), so \\( 2\\sqrt{3} + \\sqrt{3} = 3\\sqrt{3} \\)."}, {"statement": "Rationalising \\( \\dfrac{5}{\\sqrt{5}} \\) gives \\( \\sqrt{5} \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "\\( \\dfrac{5}{\\sqrt{5}} \\times \\dfrac{\\sqrt{5}}{\\sqrt{5}} = \\dfrac{5\\sqrt{5}}{5} = \\sqrt{5} \\). ✓"}, {"statement": "\\( (\\sqrt{7} - 2)(\\sqrt{7} + 2) = 3 \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "Difference of two squares: \\( (\\sqrt{7})^2 - 2^2 = 7 - 4 = 3 \\)."}, {"statement": "\\( \\dfrac{1}{3 - \\sqrt{2}} = \\dfrac{3 + \\sqrt{2}}{7} \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "Multiply by the conjugate \\( 3+\\sqrt{2} \\): denominator \\( 9 - 2 = 7 \\)."}, {"statement": "\\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 9}{x + 3} \\) simplifies to \\( x - 9 \\) by cancelling the \\( x^2 \\) and the \\( 9 \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "You may only cancel factors. Factorise first: \\( \\dfrac{(x+3)(x-3)}{x+3} = x - 3 \\)."}, {"statement": "To add \\( \\dfrac{1}{x-1} \\) and \\( \\dfrac{2}{x+1} \\) you use the common denominator \\( (x-1)(x+1) \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "Each fraction is rewritten over \\( (x-1)(x+1) \\) before the numerators are combined."}, {"statement": "On a ''detailed reasoning'' question, a correct answer straight from a calculator earns full marks.", "answer": false, "explain": "DR requires the complete method to be written out; an unexplained calculator answer scores 0 even when correct."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "\\( \\dfrac{1}{x-2} - \\dfrac{2}{x+1} = \\dfrac{-x-3}{(x-2)(x+1)} \\)", "truth": "The minus sign must multiply BOTH terms of \\( -2(x-2) = -2x + 4 \\). A weak answer writes \\( -2x - 4 \\) and gets \\( -x - 3 \\); a strong answer gets \\( x + 1 - 2x + 4 = 5 - x \\).", "check": {"question": "What is the numerator of \\( \\dfrac{1}{x-2} - \\dfrac{2}{x+1} \\)?", "options": ["\\( 5 - x \\)", "\\( -x - 3 \\)", "\\( -x - 1 \\)", "\\( x - 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( (x+1) - 2(x-2) = x + 1 - 2x + 4 = 5 - x \\)."}}, {"myth": "\\( (5 - \\sqrt{2})(5 + \\sqrt{2}) = 27 \\)", "truth": "This is a difference of two squares: \\( 25 - 2 = 23 \\), not \\( 25 + 2 = 27 \\). A weak answer adds; a strong answer subtracts, giving the denominator 23.", "check": {"question": "\\( (5 - \\sqrt{2})(5 + \\sqrt{2}) = \\)", "options": ["\\( 23 \\)", "\\( 27 \\)", "\\( 25 \\)", "\\( 5\\sqrt{2} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 5^2 - (\\sqrt{2})^2 = 25 - 2 = 23 \\)."}}, {"myth": "\\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 9}{x + 3} = x^2 - 3 \\) by cancelling the \\( x \\)", "truth": "You may only cancel FACTORS, not terms. A weak answer cancels the \\( x \\)''s; a strong answer factorises \\( (x+3)(x-3) \\) and cancels the bracket to get \\( x - 3 \\).", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( \\dfrac{x^2 - 9}{x + 3} \\).", "options": ["\\( x - 3 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 3 \\)", "\\( x - 9 \\)", "\\( x + 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Factorise the top as \\( (x+3)(x-3) \\), then cancel \\( (x+3) \\)."}}, {"myth": "\\( \\sqrt{12} + \\sqrt{27} = \\sqrt{39} \\)", "truth": "You cannot add the numbers under the root. A weak answer writes \\( \\sqrt{39} \\); a strong answer simplifies to like surds: \\( 2\\sqrt{3} + 3\\sqrt{3} = 5\\sqrt{3} \\).", "check": {"question": "\\( \\sqrt{12} + \\sqrt{27} = \\)", "options": ["\\( 5\\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{39} \\)", "\\( 6\\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{3} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 2\\sqrt{3} + 3\\sqrt{3} = 5\\sqrt{3} \\)."}}, {"myth": "Rationalising \\( \\dfrac{1}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\) by multiplying by \\( \\dfrac{2 + \\sqrt{3}}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\)", "truth": "You must use the CONJUGATE (opposite sign). A weak answer keeps \\( 2 + \\sqrt{3} \\) and does not clear the surd; a strong answer multiplies by \\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\), giving denominator \\( 4 - 3 = 1 \\) and answer \\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\).", "check": {"question": "Which multiplier rationalises \\( \\dfrac{1}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\)?", "options": ["\\( \\dfrac{2 - \\sqrt{3}}{2 - \\sqrt{3}} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{2 + \\sqrt{3}}{2 + \\sqrt{3}} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{\\sqrt{3}}{\\sqrt{3}} \\)", "\\( \\dfrac{1}{2 - \\sqrt{3}} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The conjugate \\( 2 - \\sqrt{3} \\) gives a rational denominator \\( 4 - 3 = 1 \\)."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "The ''exact'' command word", "html": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> \\( 0.696 \\) as the answer to \\( \\frac{2}{5-\\sqrt{2}} + \\frac{1}{5+\\sqrt{2}} \\) — a decimal on an \"exact\" question.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> \\( \\frac{15+\\sqrt{2}}{23} \\), the surd form. If unsure, write the exact form <em>and</em> the decimal — the exact form earns the marks and the decimal never loses them.</p>", "check": {"question": "On an ''exact'' surd question, which is safest?", "options": ["Give the surd form (optionally with the decimal)", "Give only the decimal", "Round to 3 s.f.", "Give only the decimal to 2 d.p."], "answer": 0, "explain": "The exact surd/fraction form is required; adding the decimal is harmless."}}, {"title": "The rationalising ladder", "html": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> jumping to a wrong denominator with no method.</p><p><strong>Partial:</strong> multiply by the conjugate but slip the sign to \\( 25 + 2 = 27 \\).</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> show \\( \\frac{2(5+\\sqrt{2}) + (5-\\sqrt{2})}{(5-\\sqrt{2})(5+\\sqrt{2})} \\), then \\( \\frac{15+\\sqrt{2}}{25 - 2} = \\frac{15+\\sqrt{2}}{23} \\). The unsimplified line is itself a mark.</p>", "check": {"question": "What is the correct denominator of \\( (5-\\sqrt{2})(5+\\sqrt{2}) \\)?", "options": ["\\( 23 \\)", "\\( 27 \\)", "\\( 25 \\)", "\\( 7 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 25 - 2 = 23 \\) (difference of two squares)."}}, {"title": "''Detailed reasoning'' means show every step", "html": "<p>When a question says \"<em>In this question you must show detailed reasoning</em>\", the full method must appear. On 2023 Q4(b) the examiners required the <strong>unsimplified numerator over the common denominator</strong> to be seen before the tidy answer. A correct answer with no working — even from a calculator — scores <strong>zero</strong>.</p>", "check": {"question": "For a DR rationalising question, which step must be visible?", "options": ["The unsimplified numerator over the common denominator", "Only the final answer", "A decimal check", "The calculator display"], "answer": 0, "explain": "DR credits the visible method; the unsimplified common-denominator line is the required step."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "<p>Simplify \\( \\dfrac{1}{x-2} - \\dfrac{2}{x+1} \\).</p>", "marks": 2, "hint": "Use the common denominator \\( (x-2)(x+1) \\); take care that the minus sign multiplies both terms of \\( -2(x-2) \\).", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — numerator \\( 5 - x \\) (like terms must be collected).</li>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — denominator \\( (x-2)(x+1) \\) (allow the correct quadratic \\( x^2 - x - 2 \\)).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>One mark for the correct numerator, one for the denominator; the final answer is \\( \\dfrac{5 - x}{(x-2)(x+1)} \\). Mark the final answer.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Generally answered successfully. Some did not multiply the numerators, or tried to cancel \\( x \\)''s in the final step. A common slip with the negative sign gave \\( -x - 3 \\) in the numerator instead of \\( 5 - x \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p><em>In this question you must show detailed reasoning.</em></p><p>Simplify \\( \\dfrac{2}{5 - \\sqrt{2}} + \\dfrac{1}{5 + \\sqrt{2}} \\).</p>", "marks": 3, "hint": "Multiply through by the common denominator \\( (5-\\sqrt{2})(5+\\sqrt{2}) \\), a difference of two squares — and show every line (DR).", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 3 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — unsimplified numerator seen: \\( 2(5 + \\sqrt{2}) + (5 - \\sqrt{2}) \\) over the common denominator (possibly written as two fractions with a common denominator, oe). This is the required DR step.</li>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — numerator \\( 15 + \\sqrt{2} \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — denominator \\( 23 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>Because this is detailed reasoning, the unsimplified numerator over the common denominator must be seen before simplifying; the final answer is \\( \\dfrac{15 + \\sqrt{2}}{23} \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Less successfully answered than part (a). Sign errors occurred in the numerator, and \\( 27 \\) (from \\( 25 + 2 \\)) was a popular wrong denominator instead of the correct \\( 23 \\) (from \\( 25 - 2 \\)).</li>\n            </ul></div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths', '1-3-quadratics-and-completing-the-square', '1.3 Quadratics and Completing the Square', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "What does ''completing the square'' mean?", "html": "<p><strong>Completing the square</strong> rewrites a quadratic \\( ax^2 + bx + c \\) in the form \\[ a(x + p)^2 + q. \\] The quadratic is unchanged — only its <em>shape</em> is now visible.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>It reveals the <strong>turning point</strong> (vertex) of the parabola: for \\( a(x + p)^2 + q \\) the vertex is at \\( (-p,\\ q) \\).</li>\n              <li>It lets you solve \\( ax^2 + bx + c = 0 \\) in <strong>exact form</strong> (surds), not just as a decimal.</li>\n              <li>It gives the <strong>minimum</strong> (if \\( a > 0 \\)) or <strong>maximum</strong> (if \\( a < 0 \\)) value of the quadratic — that value is \\( q \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>In this qualification you must be fluent with the general case \\( a \\ne 1 \\), which is beyond most GCSE work.</p>", "check": {"question": "For \\( 2(x-3)^2 + 5 \\), where is the turning point?", "options": ["\\( (3,\\ 5) \\)", "\\( (-3,\\ 5) \\)", "\\( (3,\\ -5) \\)", "\\( (5,\\ 3) \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The vertex of \\( a(x+p)^2+q \\) is at \\( (-p,\\ q) \\); here \\( p=-3,\\ q=5 \\), so \\( (3,\\ 5) \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you complete the square when a = 1?", "html": "<p>For \\( x^2 + bx + c \\): halve the coefficient of \\( x \\), square it, and adjust.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( x^2 + 6x - 11 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Half of \\( 6 \\) is \\( 3 \\), so start with \\( (x + 3)^2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. But \\( (x + 3)^2 = x^2 + 6x + 9 \\) — that is \\( 9 \\) too big.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Subtract \\( 9 \\), then include the \\( -11 \\): \\( (x + 3)^2 - 9 - 11 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. So \\[ x^2 + 6x - 11 = (x + 3)^2 - 20. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Check by expanding: \\( (x+3)^2 - 20 = x^2 + 6x + 9 - 20 = x^2 + 6x - 11 \\). ✓</p>", "check": {"question": "Complete the square: \\( x^2 + 8x + 3 \\).", "options": ["\\( (x+4)^2 - 13 \\)", "\\( (x+4)^2 + 3 \\)", "\\( (x+8)^2 - 13 \\)", "\\( (x+4)^2 - 19 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Half of 8 is 4; \\( (x+4)^2 = x^2+8x+16 \\), which is 16 too big, so \\( (x+4)^2 - 16 + 3 = (x+4)^2 - 13 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you complete the square when a ≠ 1?", "html": "<p>Factor the \\( a \\) out of the first two terms first, complete the square inside, then multiply back.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( 2x^2 + 12x + 5 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Factor 2 from the \\( x \\)-terms: \\( 2\\big(x^2 + 6x\\big) + 5 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Complete the square inside: \\( x^2 + 6x = (x+3)^2 - 9 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Substitute: \\( 2\\big[(x+3)^2 - 9\\big] + 5 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Expand the bracket: \\( 2(x+3)^2 - 18 + 5 = 2(x+3)^2 - 13 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So \\[ 2x^2 + 12x + 5 = 2(x + 3)^2 - 13. \\] The minimum value is \\( -13 \\), at \\( x = -3 \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "Which is the correct first step for \\( 3x^2 + 12x + 1 \\)?", "options": ["\\( 3(x^2 + 4x) + 1 \\)", "\\( 3(x^2 + 12x) + 1 \\)", "\\( (3x + 2)^2 + 1 \\)", "\\( 3(x^2 + 4x + 1) \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Factor \\( a=3 \\) from the first two terms only: \\( 3(x^2 + 4x) + 1 \\). The constant stays outside."}}, {"title": "How do you solve a quadratic in exact form?", "html": "<p>Once a quadratic is in completed-square form, solving it needs only a rearrange and a square root — and it naturally gives an <strong>exact</strong> (surd) answer.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — solve \\( x^2 + 6x - 11 = 0 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. From above: \\( (x + 3)^2 - 20 = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Rearrange: \\( (x + 3)^2 = 20 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Square root <em>both</em> signs: \\( x + 3 = \\pm\\sqrt{20} = \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. So \\[ x = -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5}. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p><strong>\"Exact\" is a command word.</strong> \\( x = -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\) is exact; \\( x = 1.47 \\) or \\( x = -7.47 \\) is <em>not</em> and scores no marks on an \"exact\" question. Writing both the exact and the decimal form is safe.</p>", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( (x - 4)^2 = 12 \\), giving exact answers.", "options": ["\\( x = 4 \\pm 2\\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( x = 4 \\pm \\sqrt{12} \\) only as a decimal", "\\( x = 4 + 2\\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( x = -4 \\pm 2\\sqrt{3} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x - 4 = \\pm\\sqrt{12} = \\pm 2\\sqrt{3} \\), so \\( x = 4 \\pm 2\\sqrt{3} \\) — both roots, simplified surd."}}, {"title": "When should you use the quadratic formula?", "html": "<p>The <strong>quadratic formula</strong> solves \\( ax^2 + bx + c = 0 \\): \\[ x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a}. \\] You must <strong>memorise</strong> it — it is not on the formula sheet.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>Use it (or completing the square) when a quadratic does not factorise nicely.</li>\n              <li>The <strong>discriminant</strong> \\( b^2 - 4ac \\) tells you how many real roots there are: \\( > 0 \\) two, \\( = 0 \\) one (repeated), \\( < 0 \\) none.</li>\n              <li>If the question says <em>\"Hence\"</em>, use the completed-square form you just found — do <strong>not</strong> restart with the formula.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>For an \"exact\" answer, leave the surd: e.g. \\( x = \\dfrac{-5 \\pm \\sqrt{13}}{2} \\), not a rounded decimal.</p>", "check": {"question": "How many real roots does \\( x^2 - 4x + 7 = 0 \\) have?", "options": ["None", "One", "Two", "Cannot tell"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( b^2 - 4ac = 16 - 28 = -12 < 0 \\), so there are no real roots."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Completing the square", "definition": "Writing \\( ax^2+bx+c \\) as \\( a(x+p)^2+q \\)."}, {"term": "Vertex of \\( a(x+p)^2+q \\)", "definition": "The turning point \\( (-p,\\ q) \\)."}, {"term": "Quadratic formula", "definition": "\\( x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2-4ac}}{2a} \\) — must be memorised."}, {"term": "Discriminant", "definition": "\\( b^2 - 4ac \\); its sign gives the number of real roots."}, {"term": "Discriminant \\( > 0 \\)", "definition": "Two distinct real roots."}, {"term": "Discriminant \\( = 0 \\)", "definition": "One repeated real root."}, {"term": "Discriminant \\( < 0 \\)", "definition": "No real roots."}, {"term": "Exact answer", "definition": "Left as a surd/fraction, e.g. \\( -3+2\\sqrt{5} \\); never a decimal."}, {"term": "Minimum value (a>0)", "definition": "The constant \\( q \\) in \\( a(x+p)^2+q \\)."}, {"term": "First step when \\( a \\ne 1 \\)", "definition": "Factor \\( a \\) from the first two terms only."}, {"term": "± when square-rooting", "definition": "Both signs, giving both roots of the equation."}, {"term": "''Hence''", "definition": "Use the result of the previous part; do not restart."}, {"term": "Half-and-square rule", "definition": "For \\( x^2+bx \\): \\( \\left(x+\\tfrac{b}{2}\\right)^2 - \\left(\\tfrac{b}{2}\\right)^2 \\)."}, {"term": "Turning point use", "definition": "Completed-square form shows the max/min and where it occurs."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Express \\( x^2 + 10x + 7 \\) in completed-square form.", "options": ["\\( (x+5)^2 - 18 \\)", "\\( (x+5)^2 + 7 \\)", "\\( (x+10)^2 - 18 \\)", "\\( (x+5)^2 - 32 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Half of 10 is 5; \\( (x+5)^2 = x^2+10x+25 \\), 25 too big, so \\( (x+5)^2 - 25 + 7 = (x+5)^2 - 18 \\)."}, {"question": "A student writes \\( x^2 + 12x - 4 = (x+6)^2 - 4 \\). What is wrong?", "options": ["They forgot to subtract \\( 36 \\): it should be \\( (x+6)^2 - 40 \\)", "Nothing — it is correct", "It should be \\( (x+12)^2 - 4 \\)", "\\( (x+6)^2 \\) should be \\( (x-6)^2 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( (x+6)^2 = x^2+12x+36 \\), so you must subtract 36 as well as keeping the \\( -4 \\): \\( (x+6)^2 - 40 \\)."}, {"question": "Complete the square for \\( 3x^2 + 6x + 1 \\).", "options": ["\\( 3(x+1)^2 - 2 \\)", "\\( 3(x+1)^2 + 1 \\)", "\\( (3x+1)^2 - 2 \\)", "\\( 3(x+1)^2 - 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 3(x^2+2x)+1 = 3[(x+1)^2 - 1] + 1 = 3(x+1)^2 - 3 + 1 = 3(x+1)^2 - 2 \\)."}, {"question": "What is the minimum value of \\( x^2 - 8x + 3 \\)?", "options": ["\\( -13 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)", "\\( -8 \\)", "\\( 13 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( (x-4)^2 - 16 + 3 = (x-4)^2 - 13 \\); the minimum is \\( -13 \\), at \\( x = 4 \\)."}, {"question": "Solve \\( (x+2)^2 = 9 \\).", "options": ["\\( x = 1 \\) or \\( x = -5 \\)", "\\( x = 1 \\) only", "\\( x = 7 \\) or \\( x = -7 \\)", "\\( x = 3 \\) or \\( x = -3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x+2 = \\pm 3 \\), so \\( x = 1 \\) or \\( x = -5 \\). You must take both signs."}, {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 + 4x - 1 = 0 \\), giving your answers in exact form.", "options": ["\\( x = -2 \\pm \\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( x = -2 \\pm \\sqrt{3} \\)", "\\( x = 2 \\pm \\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( x = -0.24 \\) or \\( x = -4.24 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( (x+2)^2 - 4 - 1 = 0 \\Rightarrow (x+2)^2 = 5 \\Rightarrow x = -2 \\pm \\sqrt{5} \\). The decimals are not ''exact''."}, {"question": "How many real solutions does \\( 2x^2 + 3x + 5 = 0 \\) have?", "options": ["None", "One", "Two", "Infinitely many"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( b^2 - 4ac = 9 - 40 = -31 < 0 \\), so no real roots."}, {"question": "Which value of \\( k \\) gives \\( x^2 + 6x + k \\) exactly one (repeated) root?", "options": ["\\( k = 9 \\)", "\\( k = 6 \\)", "\\( k = 3 \\)", "\\( k = 36 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "One root needs \\( b^2 - 4ac = 0 \\): \\( 36 - 4k = 0 \\Rightarrow k = 9 \\)."}, {"question": "In the quadratic formula, what is the discriminant?", "options": ["\\( b^2 - 4ac \\)", "\\( \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac} \\)", "\\( -b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac} \\)", "\\( 2a \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The discriminant is the part under the root, \\( b^2 - 4ac \\); its sign decides the number of real roots."}, {"question": "A question says ''Hence solve...''. What does this instruct you to do?", "options": ["Use the result you just found (the completed-square form)", "Start again with the quadratic formula", "Give the answer as a decimal", "Draw a graph"], "answer": 0, "explain": "''Hence'' means build on the previous part — here, use the completed-square form, not a fresh method."}, {"question": "Write \\( x^2 - 5x + 2 \\) in the form \\( (x+p)^2 + q \\).", "options": ["\\( \\left(x - \\tfrac{5}{2}\\right)^2 - \\tfrac{17}{4} \\)", "\\( \\left(x - \\tfrac{5}{2}\\right)^2 + 2 \\)", "\\( (x-5)^2 - 23 \\)", "\\( \\left(x - \\tfrac{5}{2}\\right)^2 - \\tfrac{25}{4} \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Half of \\( -5 \\) is \\( -\\tfrac{5}{2} \\); \\( \\left(x-\\tfrac{5}{2}\\right)^2 = x^2 - 5x + \\tfrac{25}{4} \\), so subtract \\( \\tfrac{25}{4} \\) and add 2: \\( -\\tfrac{25}{4} + \\tfrac{8}{4} = -\\tfrac{17}{4} \\)."}, {"question": "The graph of \\( y = (x-3)^2 + 4 \\) has its lowest point at:", "options": ["\\( (3,\\ 4) \\)", "\\( (-3,\\ 4) \\)", "\\( (3,\\ -4) \\)", "\\( (4,\\ 3) \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Vertex of \\( (x+p)^2 + q \\) is \\( (-p,\\ q) \\); here \\( (3,\\ 4) \\). Since \\( a>0 \\) it is a minimum."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "In the quadratic formula \\( x = \\frac{-b \\pm \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a} \\), the term before the \\( \\pm \\) sign is [-b] and the denominator is [2a]."}, {"text": "To complete the square on \\( x^2 + bx \\), take [half] the coefficient of \\( x \\) and then [square] it."}, {"text": "To complete the square on \\( x^2 + 6x - 11 \\), the number inside the bracket \\( (x + a)^2 \\) is [3] and the number subtracted at the end is [20]."}, {"text": "The expression \\( b^2 - 4ac \\) is called the [discriminant]."}, {"text": "If the discriminant is [negative], a quadratic has no real roots."}, {"text": "For \\( a(x+p)^2 + q \\) with \\( a > 0 \\), the minimum value is [q] and it occurs when \\( x \\) equals [-p]."}, {"text": "When you take the square root of both sides you must write \\( \\pm \\) to get [both] roots."}, {"text": "A command word telling you to leave surds rather than round is [exact]."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "\\( x^2 + 6x - 11 \\) can be written as \\( (x+3)^2 - 20 \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "\\( (x+3)^2 - 20 = x^2 + 6x + 9 - 20 = x^2 + 6x - 11 \\). ✓"}, {"statement": "\\( x^2 + 8x + 1 = (x+8)^2 + 1 \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "You halve the 8 to get \\( (x+4)^2 \\), and \\( (x+4)^2 = x^2+8x+16 \\), so it is \\( (x+4)^2 - 15 \\)."}, {"statement": "Giving \\( x = 1.47 \\) as the answer to an ''exact'' question earns full marks.", "answer": false, "explain": "''Exact'' requires surd/fraction form, e.g. \\( -3 + 2\\sqrt{5} \\); a decimal alone scores no marks."}, {"statement": "The equation \\( (x+2)^2 = 9 \\) has two solutions.", "answer": true, "explain": "\\( x + 2 = \\pm 3 \\), giving \\( x = 1 \\) and \\( x = -5 \\)."}, {"statement": "If \\( b^2 - 4ac = 0 \\) the quadratic has no real roots.", "answer": false, "explain": "\\( b^2 - 4ac = 0 \\) gives exactly one (repeated) real root; \\( < 0 \\) gives none."}, {"statement": "To complete the square on \\( 2x^2 + 8x + 3 \\) you first factor 2 from all three terms.", "answer": false, "explain": "Factor 2 from the first two terms only: \\( 2(x^2 + 4x) + 3 \\); the constant stays outside."}, {"statement": "The minimum value of \\( (x-4)^2 + 7 \\) is 7.", "answer": true, "explain": "A square is never negative, so the smallest value is \\( 0 + 7 = 7 \\), at \\( x = 4 \\)."}, {"statement": "The quadratic formula is printed on the exam formula sheet, so you need not memorise it.", "answer": false, "explain": "The quadratic formula is a MUST-MEMORISE formula in 6993; only the binomial series, binomial distribution, trapezium rule and kinematics relations are provided."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "\\( x^2 + 6x - 11 = (x+6)^2 - 11 \\)", "truth": "You must HALVE the coefficient of \\( x \\): it is \\( (x+3)^2 \\), not \\( (x+6)^2 \\). A weak answer copies the 6; a strong answer writes \\( (x+3)^2 - 9 - 11 = (x+3)^2 - 20 \\).", "check": {"question": "Complete the square: \\( x^2 + 6x - 11 \\).", "options": ["\\( (x+3)^2 - 20 \\)", "\\( (x+6)^2 - 11 \\)", "\\( (x+3)^2 - 11 \\)", "\\( (x+6)^2 - 47 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Halve 6 to get 3; \\( (x+3)^2 = x^2+6x+9 \\), so \\( (x+3)^2 - 9 - 11 = (x+3)^2 - 20 \\)."}}, {"myth": "Solving \\( (x+3)^2 = 20 \\) gives \\( x + 3 = \\sqrt{20} \\) only", "truth": "Taking a square root gives \\( \\pm \\). A weak answer keeps one root; a strong answer writes \\( x + 3 = \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\), so \\( x = -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\) — two roots.", "check": {"question": "\\( (x+3)^2 = 20 \\). What is \\( x \\)?", "options": ["\\( -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( -3 + 2\\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( 3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( -3 \\pm \\sqrt{20} \\) as a decimal"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x + 3 = \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\), so \\( x = -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\)."}}, {"myth": "Writing the answer to an ''exact'' question as \\( -7.47 \\) and \\( 1.47 \\)", "truth": "''Exact'' means surds/fractions kept, not decimals. A weak answer rounds; a strong answer gives \\( -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\) (and may add the decimals as a check).", "check": {"question": "Which is an ''exact'' answer?", "options": ["\\( -3 + 2\\sqrt{5} \\)", "\\( 1.47 \\)", "\\( 1.5 \\)", "about \\( 1.47 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Only the surd form \\( -3 + 2\\sqrt{5} \\) is exact."}}, {"myth": "For \\( 2x^2 + 12x + 5 \\), factoring gives \\( 2(x^2 + 6x + 5) \\)", "truth": "Only the \\( x \\)-terms are factored: \\( 2(x^2 + 6x) + 5 \\). A weak answer drags the constant inside; a strong answer keeps \\( +5 \\) outside and finishes \\( 2(x+3)^2 - 13 \\).", "check": {"question": "Correct factor step for \\( 2x^2 + 12x + 5 \\)?", "options": ["\\( 2(x^2 + 6x) + 5 \\)", "\\( 2(x^2 + 6x + 5) \\)", "\\( 2(x^2 + 12x) + 5 \\)", "\\( (2x + 6)^2 + 5 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Factor 2 from the first two terms only, leaving \\( +5 \\) outside."}}, {"myth": "\\( x^2 - 4x + 9 = 0 \\) must have solutions because it is a quadratic", "truth": "Not every quadratic has real roots. A weak answer assumes two roots; a strong answer checks the discriminant: \\( 16 - 36 = -20 < 0 \\), so there are no real roots.", "check": {"question": "How many real roots has \\( x^2 - 4x + 9 = 0 \\)?", "options": ["None", "One", "Two", "Three"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( b^2 - 4ac = 16 - 36 = -20 < 0 \\Rightarrow \\) no real roots."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "The ''exact'' command word", "html": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> \\( x = 1.47,\\ -7.47 \\) on an \"exact\" question — decimals only.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> \\( x = -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\). If unsure, write the exact form <em>and</em> the decimal — the exact form earns the marks and the decimal never loses them.</p>", "check": {"question": "On an ''exact'' question, which is safest?", "options": ["Give the surd form (optionally with the decimal)", "Give only the decimal", "Round to 2 d.p.", "Give only the decimal to 3 s.f."], "answer": 0, "explain": "The exact surd form is required; adding the decimal is harmless."}}, {"title": "Show every step (method marks)", "html": "<p>For \"complete the square\" [3]: examiners award <strong>B1</strong> for \\( (x+3)^2 \\), <strong>M1</strong> for adjusting the constant, <strong>A1</strong> for the final \\( (x+3)^2 - 20 \\). Write each line so a slip costs one mark, not all three.</p>", "check": {"question": "Why write out each line of working?", "options": ["To earn method marks even if the final answer slips", "It is not necessary", "To use more paper", "To slow down"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Method (M) and intermediate (B/A) marks are awarded for visible correct steps."}}, {"title": "''Hence'' means reuse part (a)", "html": "<p>If part (b) says \"<em>Hence</em> solve \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\)\", start from your completed-square form \\( (x+3)^2 - 20 = 0 \\) — do <strong>not</strong> reach for the quadratic formula. The 2024 examiners noted candidates who restarted (or converted back to the original) wasted time and risked errors.</p>", "check": {"question": "Part (b) says ''Hence solve''. You should:", "options": ["Use your part (a) completed-square form", "Use the quadratic formula from scratch", "Factorise by trial", "Draw a graph and read off"], "answer": 0, "explain": "''Hence'' directs you to build on part (a)."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "<p>Express \\( \\text{f}(x) \\) in the form \\( (x + a)^2 + b \\).</p>", "marks": 3, "hint": "Halve the coefficient of \\( x \\) for \\( a \\); adjust the constant for \\( b \\).", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 3 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — sight of \\( (x + 3)^2 \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — attempt to find the constant using their \\( (x + 3)^2 \\) (i.e. subtract 9, keep the \\( -11 \\)).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — \\( (x + 3)^2 - 20 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>The three marks are for the bracket, the adjustment, and the final exact constant respectively.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Well answered by most; a small minority used \\( (x + 6)^2 \\) instead of \\( (x + 3)^2 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>Hence solve the equation \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\), giving your answers in exact form.</p>", "marks": 2, "hint": "Start from your part (a) form — set it equal to 0 and square-root both sides (remember \\( \\pm \\)).", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — set equal to 0 and take the square root using their expression from (a): \\( (x+3)^2 = 20 \\Rightarrow x + 3 = \\pm\\sqrt{20} \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — \\( x = -3 \\pm 2\\sqrt{5} \\) (cao; allow other exact surd forms, isw).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>One correct root only is M1 A0. Correct roots with no wrong working score B2.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>\"Hence\" signalled that part (a) should be used, but some restarted with the quadratic formula. A significant minority did not understand \"exact\"; those who gave both the exact and the decimal form were fine.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths', '1-4-linear-and-quadratic-inequalities', '1.4 Linear and Quadratic Inequalities', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "What does it mean to solve an inequality?", "html": "<p>An <strong>inequality</strong> compares two expressions with \\( < \\) (less than), \\( > \\) (greater than), \\( \\le \\) (less than or equal to) or \\( \\ge \\) (greater than or equal to). Solving one means finding <strong>every</strong> value of the variable that makes it true — usually a <strong>range</strong> of values, not a single number.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>The answer is a <strong>solution set</strong>, e.g. \\( x < 4 \\) or \\( -2 \\le x \\le 3 \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Strict</strong> inequalities (\\( < \\), \\( > \\)) exclude the end value; <strong>non-strict</strong> ones (\\( \\le \\), \\( \\ge \\)) include it.</li>\n              <li>You can picture a solution set on a <strong>number line</strong> — an <strong>open</strong> circle for a value that is excluded, a <strong>closed</strong> (filled) circle for one that is included.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Most of the algebra you already use for equations works for inequalities too — with <strong>one crucial exception</strong> that costs marks every year (next card).</p>", "check": {"question": "Which describes the solution set \\( -2 \\le x \\le 3 \\)?", "options": ["Every \\( x \\) from \\( -2 \\) to \\( 3 \\), both ends included", "Only \\( x = -2 \\) and \\( x = 3 \\)", "Every \\( x \\) from \\( -2 \\) to \\( 3 \\), both ends excluded", "Only whole numbers between \\( -2 \\) and \\( 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The \\( \\le \\) signs are non-strict, so both \\( -2 \\) and \\( 3 \\) are included, along with every real number between them."}}, {"title": "When you manipulate an inequality, when does the sign flip?", "html": "<p>You may do the same thing to <strong>both sides</strong> of an inequality — but watch the sign:</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Add or subtract</strong> any number: the sign <strong>never</strong> changes.</li>\n              <li><strong>Multiply or divide by a positive</strong> number: the sign <strong>never</strong> changes.</li>\n              <li><strong>Multiply or divide by a negative</strong> number: you <strong>must reverse (flip) the inequality sign.</strong></li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Why? Because \\( 2 < 5 \\) is true, but multiplying by \\( -1 \\) gives \\( -2 \\) and \\( -5 \\), and \\( -2 > -5 \\) — the order reverses.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — solve \\( 5 - 2x \\ge 11 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Subtract 5 from both sides: \\( -2x \\ge 6 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Divide both sides by \\( -2 \\) — this is division by a <em>negative</em>, so FLIP the sign: \\( x \\le -3 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Check with \\( x = -4 \\): \\( 5 - 2(-4) = 13 \\ge 11 \\) ✓. The <strong>#1 examiner-reported error</strong> is reaching \\( -x > 6 \\) and writing \\( x > -6 \\) instead of \\( x < -6 \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( -3x > 12 \\).", "options": ["\\( x > 4 \\)", "\\( x < -4 \\)", "\\( x > -4 \\)", "\\( x < 4 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Divide both sides by \\( -3 \\); because \\( -3 \\) is negative, the sign flips, giving \\( x < -4 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you solve a double (''sandwich'') inequality?", "html": "<p>A <strong>double</strong> (or \"sandwich\") inequality such as \\( \\frac{1}{3} < \\frac{2x-1}{5} < 1 \\) traps one expression between two bounds. The rule is simple: whatever you do, <strong>do it to all three parts at once.</strong></p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — solve \\( \\frac{1}{3} < \\frac{2x-1}{5} < 1 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Multiply <em>all three</em> parts by 5: \\( \\frac{5}{3} < 2x - 1 < 5 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Add 1 to all three parts: \\( \\frac{8}{3} < 2x < 6 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Divide all three parts by 2: \\( \\frac{4}{3} < x < 3 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the solution is \\( \\frac{4}{3} < x < 3 \\). If you ever multiply or divide the parts by a negative, flip <strong>both</strong> signs and rewrite the chain in ascending order. Taking the two inequalities separately is fine too — just recombine the answers at the end.</p>", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( -1 < 2x + 3 < 9 \\).", "options": ["\\( -2 < x < 3 \\)", "\\( -1 < x < 9 \\)", "\\( -2 < x < 6 \\)", "\\( 1 < x < 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Subtract 3 from all three parts: \\( -4 < 2x < 6 \\); divide all three by 2: \\( -2 < x < 3 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you solve a quadratic inequality algebraically?", "html": "<p>A <strong>quadratic inequality</strong> such as \\( x^2 - x - 6 > 0 \\) is solved in four steps:</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Rearrange so one side is <strong>0</strong> (here it already is).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. <strong>Factorise</strong>: \\( x^2 - x - 6 = (x - 3)(x + 2) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Find the <strong>critical values</strong> — the roots where the quadratic \\( = 0 \\): \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( x = -2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Decide which region satisfies the inequality (sketch the parabola — next card).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The graph of \\( y = x^2 - x - 6 \\) is a parabola opening <strong>upwards</strong> (because the \\( x^2 \\) coefficient is positive). It is <strong>above</strong> the \\( x \\)-axis (\\( y > 0 \\)) <em>outside</em> the roots, and <strong>below</strong> it (\\( y < 0 \\)) <em>between</em> the roots. So:</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>\\( x^2 - x - 6 > 0 \\Rightarrow x < -2 \\ \\) or \\( \\ x > 3 \\).</li>\n              <li>\\( x^2 - x - 6 < 0 \\Rightarrow -2 < x < 3 \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Never</strong> just \"square-root and solve like an equation\" — a quadratic inequality almost always has a two-part answer.</p>", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 - x - 6 > 0 \\).", "options": ["\\( -2 < x < 3 \\)", "\\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)", "\\( x < -3 \\) or \\( x > 2 \\)", "\\( x > 3 \\) only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The upward parabola is above the axis outside its roots \\( -2 \\) and \\( 3 \\), so \\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you read the region off a sketch of the parabola?", "html": "<p>The safest way to get the region right is to <strong>sketch the parabola and see where it is above or below the \\( x \\)-axis.</strong> You only need a rough sketch showing which way it opens and where it crosses the axis (the critical values).</p>\n            <p>For \\( y = x^2 - x - 6 = (x-3)(x+2) \\), the curve opens upwards and crosses at \\( x = -2 \\) and \\( x = 3 \\):</p>\n            <svg viewBox=\"0 0 300 190\" width=\"100%\" style=\"max-width:340px;height:auto;display:block;margin:14px auto\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Upward parabola crossing the x-axis at minus 2 and 3, dipping below the axis between them\">\n              <line x1=\"20\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"285\" y2=\"120\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n              <polygon points=\"285,120 276,116 276,124\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n              <line x1=\"110\" y1=\"120\" x2=\"190\" y2=\"120\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"6\" stroke-opacity=\"0.35\"/>\n              <path d=\"M 55,25 Q 150,255 245,25\" fill=\"none\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"2.5\"/>\n              <circle cx=\"110\" cy=\"120\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n              <circle cx=\"190\" cy=\"120\" r=\"4\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n              <text x=\"110\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"14\" fill=\"currentColor\">-2</text>\n              <text x=\"190\" y=\"140\" text-anchor=\"middle\" font-size=\"14\" fill=\"currentColor\">3</text>\n              <text x=\"278\" y=\"112\" text-anchor=\"end\" font-size=\"13\" fill=\"currentColor\">x</text>\n            </svg>\n            <ul>\n              <li>Want \\( y < 0 \\) (curve <strong>below</strong> the axis, shaded)? Read off the region <em>between</em> the roots: \\( -2 < x < 3 \\).</li>\n              <li>Want \\( y > 0 \\) (curve <strong>above</strong> the axis)? Read off the two \"arms\" <em>outside</em> the roots: \\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>If the parabola opened downwards (negative \\( x^2 \\) coefficient), the \"above/below\" regions simply swap.</p>", "check": {"question": "Using the sketch, solve \\( x^2 - x - 6 \\le 0 \\).", "options": ["\\( x \\le -2 \\) or \\( x \\ge 3 \\)", "\\( -2 \\le x \\le 3 \\)", "\\( -3 \\le x \\le 2 \\)", "\\( x \\le 3 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( \\le 0 \\) means on or below the axis — the region between (and including) the roots: \\( -2 \\le x \\le 3 \\)."}}, {"title": "Why is \\( x^2 > 9 \\) not just \\( x > 3 \\)?", "html": "<p>A very common slip is to \"square-root both sides\" of \\( x^2 > 9 \\) and write \\( x > 3 \\). That misses <strong>half</strong> the answer, because a negative number can also have a large square: \\( (-5)^2 = 25 > 9 \\).</p>\n            <p>Treat it as a <strong>quadratic inequality</strong>:</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Rearrange to one side: \\( x^2 - 9 > 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Factorise (difference of two squares): \\( (x - 3)(x + 3) > 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Critical values \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( x = -3 \\); the upward parabola is above the axis outside the roots.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. So \\( x < -3 \\ \\) or \\( \\ x > 3 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The mirror-image case is just as important: \\( x^2 < 9 \\) gives \\( -3 < x < 3 \\) (between the roots). In general, for \\( a > 0 \\): \\( x^2 > a^2 \\Rightarrow x < -a \\) or \\( x > a \\); and \\( x^2 < a^2 \\Rightarrow -a < x < a \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 > 25 \\).", "options": ["\\( x > 5 \\) only", "\\( x < -5 \\) or \\( x > 5 \\)", "\\( -5 < x < 5 \\)", "\\( x > 5 \\) or \\( x > -5 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( x^2 - 25 > 0 \\Rightarrow (x-5)(x+5) > 0 \\); the region outside the roots is \\( x < -5 \\) or \\( x > 5 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you show a solution set on a number line?", "html": "<p>Marking a solution on a <strong>number line</strong> is a real exam skill (OCR 2019 Q2b). Two things must be right:</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>The <strong>line/region</strong> covers exactly the solution set.</li>\n              <li>The <strong>circles</strong> at the ends show whether each end value is included: <strong>closed (filled)</strong> for \\( \\le \\) / \\( \\ge \\), <strong>open (empty)</strong> for \\( < \\) / \\( > \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — illustrate \\( -3 \\le x \\le 4 \\):</strong> a line from \\( -3 \\) to \\( 4 \\) with <strong>filled</strong> circles at both ends (both included):</p>\n            <svg viewBox=\"0 0 420 64\" width=\"100%\" style=\"max-width:460px;height:auto;display:block;margin:14px auto\" role=\"img\" aria-label=\"Number line showing minus 3 less than or equal to x less than or equal to 4 with closed circles at minus 3 and 4\">\n              <line x1=\"20\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"405\" y2=\"30\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1.5\"/>\n              <line x1=\"66\" y1=\"30\" x2=\"318\" y2=\"30\" stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"6\" stroke-opacity=\"0.35\"/>\n              <g stroke=\"currentColor\" stroke-width=\"1\">\n                <line x1=\"30\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"30\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"66\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"66\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"102\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"102\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"138\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"138\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"174\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"174\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"210\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"210\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"246\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"246\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"282\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"282\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"318\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"318\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"354\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"354\" y2=\"35\"/><line x1=\"390\" y1=\"25\" x2=\"390\" y2=\"35\"/>\n              </g>\n              <g font-size=\"12\" fill=\"currentColor\" text-anchor=\"middle\">\n                <text x=\"30\" y=\"52\">-4</text><text x=\"66\" y=\"52\">-3</text><text x=\"102\" y=\"52\">-2</text><text x=\"138\" y=\"52\">-1</text><text x=\"174\" y=\"52\">0</text><text x=\"210\" y=\"52\">1</text><text x=\"246\" y=\"52\">2</text><text x=\"282\" y=\"52\">3</text><text x=\"318\" y=\"52\">4</text><text x=\"354\" y=\"52\">5</text><text x=\"390\" y=\"52\">6</text>\n              </g>\n              <circle cx=\"66\" cy=\"30\" r=\"5.5\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n              <circle cx=\"318\" cy=\"30\" r=\"5.5\" fill=\"currentColor\"/>\n            </svg>\n            <p>If the inequality had been \\( -3 < x < 4 \\) (strict), the two end circles would be drawn <strong>open</strong> (empty) instead. Examiners warn every year that an ambiguous circle — neither clearly filled nor clearly empty — loses the mark.</p>", "check": {"question": "To show \\( x > 2 \\) on a number line, the circle at \\( 2 \\) should be:", "options": ["closed (filled), with the line going left", "open (empty), with the line going right", "closed (filled), with the line going right", "open (empty), with the line going left"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( > \\) is strict, so \\( 2 \\) is excluded — an open circle — and \\( x > 2 \\) points to larger values, so the line goes right."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Inequality", "definition": "A statement comparing expressions with \\( <, >, \\le \\) or \\( \\ge \\)."}, {"term": "Solution set", "definition": "Every value of the variable that makes the inequality true — usually a range."}, {"term": "Golden rule (× or ÷ by a negative)", "definition": "Reverse (flip) the inequality sign."}, {"term": "Add / subtract rule", "definition": "Adding or subtracting the same number never changes the sign''s direction."}, {"term": "Double (sandwich) inequality", "definition": "Apply every operation to all three parts at once."}, {"term": "Strict inequality", "definition": "\\( < \\) or \\( > \\); end value excluded; open circle."}, {"term": "Non-strict inequality", "definition": "\\( \\le \\) or \\( \\ge \\); end value included; closed circle."}, {"term": "Open circle", "definition": "On a number line, marks an end value that is NOT included."}, {"term": "Closed (filled) circle", "definition": "On a number line, marks an end value that IS included."}, {"term": "Quadratic inequality method", "definition": "One side \\( = 0 \\), factorise, find critical values, sketch, read the region."}, {"term": "Critical values", "definition": "The roots where the quadratic equals zero — the region boundaries."}, {"term": "Upward parabola \\( > 0 \\)", "definition": "Solution is OUTSIDE the roots (the two arms)."}, {"term": "Upward parabola \\( < 0 \\)", "definition": "Solution is BETWEEN the roots."}, {"term": "\\( x^2 > 9 \\)", "definition": "\\( x < -3 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\) — not just \\( x > 3 \\)."}, {"term": "\\( x^2 < a^2 \\) (a > 0)", "definition": "\\( -a < x < a \\)."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Solve \\( 3x - 5 < 7 \\).", "options": ["\\( x > 4 \\)", "\\( x < 4 \\)", "\\( x < 12 \\)", "\\( x < 2 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Add 5: \\( 3x < 12 \\); divide by 3 (positive, no flip): \\( x < 4 \\)."}, {"question": "Solve \\( -2x > 8 \\).", "options": ["\\( x > -4 \\)", "\\( x > 4 \\)", "\\( x < -4 \\)", "\\( x < 4 \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Divide by \\( -2 \\); dividing by a negative flips the sign, giving \\( x < -4 \\)."}, {"question": "Solve \\( 5 - 2x \\ge 11 \\).", "options": ["\\( x \\le -3 \\)", "\\( x \\ge -3 \\)", "\\( x \\le 3 \\)", "\\( x \\ge 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Subtract 5: \\( -2x \\ge 6 \\); divide by \\( -2 \\) and flip: \\( x \\le -3 \\)."}, {"question": "Solve the double inequality \\( \\frac{1}{3} < \\frac{2x-1}{5} < 1 \\).", "options": ["\\( \\frac{4}{3} < x < 3 \\)", "\\( \\frac{2}{3} < x < 3 \\)", "\\( \\frac{4}{3} < x < 2 \\)", "\\( 1 < x < 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Multiply all three parts by 5: \\( \\frac{5}{3} < 2x-1 < 5 \\); add 1: \\( \\frac{8}{3} < 2x < 6 \\); divide by 2: \\( \\frac{4}{3} < x < 3 \\)."}, {"question": "Solve \\( -4 < 3x + 2 \\le 11 \\).", "options": ["\\( -2 < x \\le 3 \\)", "\\( -2 \\le x < 3 \\)", "\\( 2 < x \\le 3 \\)", "\\( -6 < x \\le 9 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Subtract 2 from all parts: \\( -6 < 3x \\le 9 \\); divide by 3: \\( -2 < x \\le 3 \\). Option D forgot to divide by 3."}, {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 - x - 6 > 0 \\).", "options": ["\\( -2 < x < 3 \\)", "\\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)", "\\( x < -3 \\) or \\( x > 2 \\)", "\\( x > 3 \\) only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( (x-3)(x+2) > 0 \\); the upward parabola is above the axis outside its roots, so \\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)."}, {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 - x - 6 \\le 0 \\).", "options": ["\\( x \\le -2 \\) or \\( x \\ge 3 \\)", "\\( -3 \\le x \\le 2 \\)", "\\( -2 \\le x \\le 3 \\)", "\\( 2 \\le x \\le 3 \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "\\( \\le 0 \\) is the region on or below the axis, between the roots: \\( -2 \\le x \\le 3 \\)."}, {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 > 9 \\).", "options": ["\\( x > 3 \\)", "\\( x < -3 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)", "\\( -3 < x < 3 \\)", "\\( x > 3 \\) or \\( x > -3 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( x^2 - 9 > 0 \\Rightarrow (x-3)(x+3) > 0 \\); outside the roots: \\( x < -3 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\). Writing just \\( x > 3 \\) misses the negative arm."}, {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 \\le 16 \\).", "options": ["\\( -4 \\le x \\le 4 \\)", "\\( x \\le 4 \\)", "\\( x \\le -4 \\) or \\( x \\ge 4 \\)", "\\( 0 \\le x \\le 4 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x^2 - 16 \\le 0 \\Rightarrow (x-4)(x+4) \\le 0 \\); the region between the roots (inclusive) is \\( -4 \\le x \\le 4 \\)."}, {"question": "The critical values for \\( x^2 + 2x - 15 \\ge 0 \\) are:", "options": ["\\( x = 5 \\) and \\( x = -3 \\)", "\\( x = -5 \\) and \\( x = 3 \\)", "\\( x = 15 \\) and \\( x = 1 \\)", "\\( x = -2 \\) and \\( x = 15 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( x^2 + 2x - 15 = (x+5)(x-3) \\), so the roots (critical values) are \\( x = -5 \\) and \\( x = 3 \\)."}, {"question": "On a number line, the solution \\( -1 \\le x < 4 \\) is drawn with:", "options": ["an open circle at \\( -1 \\) and a closed circle at \\( 4 \\)", "a closed circle at \\( -1 \\) and an open circle at \\( 4 \\)", "closed circles at both ends", "open circles at both ends"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( \\le \\) at \\( -1 \\) means it is included (closed); \\( < \\) at \\( 4 \\) means it is excluded (open)."}, {"question": "A rectangle has width \\( x \\) cm and area \\( x(x+2) \\) cm², which must be less than 15 cm². For what widths does this hold?", "options": ["\\( 0 < x < 3 \\)", "\\( -5 < x < 3 \\)", "\\( x < 3 \\)", "\\( x > 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x^2 + 2x - 15 < 0 \\Rightarrow (x+5)(x-3) < 0 \\Rightarrow -5 < x < 3 \\); but a width must be positive, so \\( 0 < x < 3 \\)."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "When you multiply or divide an inequality by a negative number you must [reverse] the direction of the inequality sign."}, {"text": "Adding or subtracting the same quantity from both sides [keeps] the direction of the inequality sign."}, {"text": "To solve a quadratic inequality, first rearrange it so that one side equals [zero], then factorise."}, {"text": "The quadratic \\( x^2 - x - 6 \\) factorises to \\( (x-3)(x+2) \\), so its critical values are \\( 3 \\) and [-2]."}, {"text": "For an upward-opening parabola, \\( ax^2 + bx + c < 0 \\) is satisfied [between] the two critical values."}, {"text": "For an upward-opening parabola, \\( ax^2 + bx + c > 0 \\) is satisfied [outside] the two critical values."}, {"text": "A strict inequality such as \\( < \\) or \\( > \\) is shown on a number line with an [open] circle."}, {"text": "The solution to \\( x^2 > 9 \\) is \\( x < -3 \\) [or] \\( x > 3 \\)."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "Multiplying or dividing both sides of an inequality by a negative number reverses the inequality sign.", "answer": true, "explain": "Correct — e.g. from \\( 2 < 5 \\), multiplying by \\( -1 \\) gives \\( -2 > -5 \\); the order reverses."}, {"statement": "\\( -x > 6 \\) is the same as \\( x > -6 \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "Dividing \\( -x > 6 \\) by \\( -1 \\) flips the sign, giving \\( x < -6 \\), not \\( x > -6 \\). This is the classic 2024 Q1 error."}, {"statement": "To solve \\( \\frac{1}{3} < \\frac{2x-1}{5} < 1 \\) you may operate on all three parts at once.", "answer": true, "explain": "Yes — whatever you do (×5, +1, ÷2) you do to every part of the sandwich inequality."}, {"statement": "The inequality \\( x^2 > 9 \\) has solution \\( x > 3 \\) only.", "answer": false, "explain": "It is \\( (x-3)(x+3) > 0 \\Rightarrow x < -3 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\); a negative such as \\( -5 \\) also satisfies it."}, {"statement": "For \\( x^2 - x - 6 < 0 \\), because the parabola opens upwards the solution lies between the roots.", "answer": true, "explain": "An upward parabola is below the axis (\\( y < 0 \\)) between its roots, so \\( -2 < x < 3 \\)."}, {"statement": "A closed (filled) circle on a number line shows that the end value is included (\\( \\le \\) or \\( \\ge \\)).", "answer": true, "explain": "Correct; an open circle is used for strict inequalities (\\( < \\) or \\( > \\)) where the end value is excluded."}, {"statement": "Adding the same number to both sides of an inequality can change the direction of the sign.", "answer": false, "explain": "Only multiplying/dividing by a negative flips the sign; adding or subtracting never does."}, {"statement": "Multiplying the double inequality \\( -1 < x < 4 \\) by \\( -2 \\) gives \\( -8 < -2x < 2 \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "Multiplying by \\( -2 \\) and flipping both signs gives \\( 2 > -2x > -8 \\), which is the same as \\( -8 < -2x < 2 \\)."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "\\( -x > 6 \\Rightarrow x > -6 \\)", "truth": "Dividing by \\( -1 \\) must FLIP the sign. A weak answer keeps \\( > \\); a strong answer writes \\( x < -6 \\). This was the exemplar error of OCR 2024 Q1 — much of the algebra was correct but candidates could not deal with the final negative.", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( 2 - (x+1) > 7 \\).", "options": ["\\( x > -6 \\)", "\\( x < -6 \\)", "\\( x > 6 \\)", "\\( x < 6 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( 2 - x - 1 > 7 \\Rightarrow 1 - x > 7 \\Rightarrow -x > 6 \\); divide by \\( -1 \\) and flip: \\( x < -6 \\)."}}, {"myth": "\\( x^2 > 9 \\Rightarrow x > 3 \\)", "truth": "Square-rooting loses the negative arm. A weak answer gives \\( x > 3 \\) only; a strong answer treats it as \\( (x-3)(x+3) > 0 \\) and writes \\( x < -3 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\).", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( x^2 > 16 \\).", "options": ["\\( x > 4 \\) only", "\\( x < -4 \\) or \\( x > 4 \\)", "\\( -4 < x < 4 \\)", "\\( x < 4 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( (x-4)(x+4) > 0 \\); outside the roots: \\( x < -4 \\) or \\( x > 4 \\)."}}, {"myth": "\\( x^2 - x - 6 > 0 \\Rightarrow -2 < x < 3 \\)", "truth": "That is the region for \\( < 0 \\), not \\( > 0 \\). A weak answer picks the wrong region; a strong answer sketches the upward parabola and reads the region ABOVE the axis: \\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\).", "check": {"question": "Which region makes an upward parabola positive (\\( y > 0 \\))?", "options": ["Between the roots", "Outside the roots", "At the roots only", "Everywhere"], "answer": 1, "explain": "An upward parabola is above the axis (positive) outside its two roots."}}, {"myth": "Solving \\( \\frac{2x-1}{5} < 1 \\) by adding 1 to only the middle part of a double inequality", "truth": "Every operation must be applied to ALL THREE parts. A weak answer changes one part; a strong answer keeps the chain balanced: multiply all three by 5, add 1 to all three, divide all three by 2.", "check": {"question": "When solving \\( \\frac{1}{3} < \\frac{2x-1}{5} < 1 \\), what do you multiply by 5?", "options": ["Only the middle part", "All three parts", "Only the outer two parts", "Nothing — you cannot multiply"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A double inequality is kept true only if every part receives the same operation."}}, {"myth": "Drawing an OPEN circle to show \\( x \\le 4 \\) on a number line", "truth": "\\( \\le \\) includes the end value, so the circle must be CLOSED (filled). A weak answer leaves it open or ambiguous; a strong answer fills it clearly. OCR 2019 Q2b noted markers could not always tell whether a circle was filled in.", "check": {"question": "For \\( x \\ge -1 \\), the circle at \\( -1 \\) should be:", "options": ["open (empty)", "closed (filled)", "half-shaded", "a cross"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( \\ge \\) is non-strict, so \\( -1 \\) is included and the circle is closed (filled)."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "The negative-flip trap (a guaranteed exam mark)", "html": "<p>OCR 2024 Q1 asked to solve \\( 2 - (x+1) > 7 \\).</p><p><strong>0 / 2 marks:</strong> correct algebra down to \\( -x > 6 \\), then \\( x > -6 \\) — the sign was not flipped.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> \\( -x > 6 \\Rightarrow x < -6 \\). Whenever you divide (or multiply) by a negative, flip the sign and, if you like, sanity-check one value: \\( x = -10 \\) gives \\( 2 - (-9) = 11 > 7 \\) ✓.</p>", "check": {"question": "You reach \\( -x > 6 \\). The correct final line is:", "options": ["\\( x > -6 \\)", "\\( x < -6 \\)", "\\( x > 6 \\)", "\\( x < 6 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Multiplying by \\( -1 \\) flips \\( > \\) to \\( < \\): \\( x < -6 \\)."}}, {"title": "A ladder for quadratic inequalities", "html": "<p>Score every mark on a quadratic inequality with the same four steps:</p><p><strong>1.</strong> Make one side \\( 0 \\). <strong>2.</strong> Factorise to find the critical values. <strong>3.</strong> Sketch the parabola (which way it opens + where it crosses). <strong>4.</strong> Read the region.</p><p>Write \"\\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)\" — NOT \"\\( -2 > x > 3 \\)\", which is impossible. A quick sketch beside your working is the surest guard against choosing the wrong region.</p>", "check": {"question": "For a quadratic inequality, what should you find right after making one side zero?", "options": ["The turning point", "The critical values (roots)", "The discriminant''s sign", "The y-intercept"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Factorising to the critical values (roots) is step 2; the sketch then tells you the region."}}, {"title": "Present the solution set clearly", "html": "<p>Communication marks are lost on presentation, not maths.</p><p>Use \"<strong>or</strong>\" for a two-part answer (\\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)) and \"<strong>and</strong>\"/a single chain for a between-answer (\\( -2 \\le x \\le 3 \\)). On a number line, make circles unmistakably <strong>open</strong> (strict) or <strong>closed</strong> (non-strict) — OCR 2019 Q2b penalised ambiguous circles.</p>", "check": {"question": "Which is the correct way to write the solution of \\( x^2 - x - 6 > 0 \\)?", "options": ["\\( -2 > x > 3 \\)", "\\( x < -2 \\) or \\( x > 3 \\)", "\\( -2 < x < 3 \\)", "\\( x < -2 \\) and \\( x > 3 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The two separate arms are joined by ''or''; \\( -2 > x > 3 \\) is impossible and ''and'' would describe no values."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "<p>Solve the inequality \\( 2 - (x + 1) > 7 \\).</p>", "marks": 2, "hint": "Expand and collect first; when you divide by a negative, remember to flip the inequality sign.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — Correct 1st step, e.g. removal of brackets or collecting like terms or subtracting 2 from both sides.</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — \\( x < -6 \\) (accept \\( -6 > x \\)).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>The method mark is for a correct manipulation; the accuracy mark requires the sign to be reversed correctly when dividing by \\( -1 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>This proved to be an easy start to the paper. However, not all candidates obtained full marks. The main error occurred when candidates obtained the answer \\( -x > 6 \\) but were unable to manipulate this correctly to give \\( x < -6 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>Solve the inequality \\( x^2 - x - 12 \\le 0 \\).</p>", "marks": 3, "hint": "Factorise to find the critical values, then sketch the upward parabola to read the region.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 3 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — For factorisation into \\( (x-4)(x+3) \\) (soi).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — Correct end (critical) values \\( -3 \\) and \\( 4 \\) (soi).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — Correct inequality \\( -3 \\le x \\le 4 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>Accept \"\\( -3 \\le x \\) and \\( x \\le 4 \\)\" only for the final mark — not a comma, \"or\", spaces, or the two parts on different lines.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Very few candidates did not factorise the quadratic function properly and most obtained the correct inequality.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>Illustrate your answer to part (a) on a number line.</p><p><em>(Describe what you would draw: the region and the two end-point circles.)</em></p>", "marks": 2, "hint": "The inequality is non-strict (\\( \\le \\)), so both end values are included — think about which kind of circle that needs.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — One line drawn between the two end points \\( -3 \\) and \\( 4 \\) (or ft from part (a)).</li>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — Filled (closed) circles at the end points of the line. (The two B marks are independent.)</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>The examiner must be convinced the circles are filled, not empty. Because part (a) is \\( \\le \\) (non-strict), closed circles are required.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>A number of candidates seemed unaware of the difference between filling in the circles at the ends of the number line and not filling them in. In a few cases this led to an uncertainty as to whether the circles had been filled in or not. There were also a few non-standard presentations of the inequality on the number line.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>Solve the inequality \\( -3 < 2(x + 1) < 7 \\).</p>", "marks": 3, "hint": "This is a double inequality — apply each operation to all three parts, keeping the chain balanced.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 3 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — Correct first operation on at least one side to solve the inequality (e.g. expand to \\( -3 < 2x + 2 < 7 \\)).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — For a correct inequality on both sides involving \\( 2x \\) or \\( x+1 \\) (soi), e.g. \\( -5 < 2x < 5 \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — \\( -\\frac{5}{2} < x < \\frac{5}{2} \\) (accept \\( -2.5 < x < 2.5 \\), isw).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>If the answer is given as two separate inequalities they must be joined by \"and\" for the last mark. SC3 for a correct answer with no wrong working (use of \"=\" is allowed provided the final answer is correct).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Candidates who did well took the inequality as a whole and added, subtracted or divided across the three parts. Some took the two inequalities separately, which was acceptable provided the solutions were put together again. Replacing the inequalities by an equals sign can be a dangerous process, particularly when dividing by numbers.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths', '2-1-polynomial-arithmetic-and-division', '2.1 Polynomial Arithmetic and Division', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "What is a polynomial, and what do we call its parts?", "html": "<p>A <strong>polynomial</strong> is a sum of terms of the form \\( a x^n \\), where the powers \\( n \\) are whole numbers \\( (0, 1, 2, 3, \\dots) \\). For example \\( 2x^3 - 5x^2 + x - 4 \\) is a polynomial; \\( \\dfrac{1}{x} \\) and \\( \\sqrt{x} \\) are <em>not</em> (their powers are \\( -1 \\) and \\( \\tfrac{1}{2} \\)).</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>The <strong>degree</strong> is the highest power of \\( x \\). \\( 2x^3 - 5x^2 + x - 4 \\) has degree 3 (a <em>cubic</em>); degree 2 is a <em>quadratic</em>, degree 1 is <em>linear</em>.</li>\n              <li>A <strong>coefficient</strong> is the number multiplying a power of \\( x \\) — here the coefficient of \\( x^2 \\) is \\( -5 \\).</li>\n              <li>The number on its own (\\( -4 \\)) is the <strong>constant term</strong>.</li>\n              <li>Write polynomials in <strong>descending order</strong> — highest power first — so the arithmetic lines up neatly.</li>\n              <li>Only <strong>like terms</strong> (same power of \\( x \\)) can be combined: \\( 3x^2 \\) and \\( 5x^2 \\) add to \\( 8x^2 \\), but \\( 3x^2 \\) and \\( 5x \\) stay apart.</li>\n            </ul>", "check": {"question": "What is the degree of \\( 4x^5 - 2x^2 + 7 \\)?", "options": ["5", "4", "2", "7"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The degree is the highest power of \\( x \\), which is \\( 5 \\). The constant \\( 7 \\) has power \\( 0 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you add and subtract polynomials?", "html": "<p>Collect <strong>like terms</strong> — line up equal powers of \\( x \\) and combine their coefficients. For <strong>subtraction</strong>, the single biggest trap is the minus sign: it must be applied to <em>every</em> term in the second bracket.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( (5x^2 - 3x + 2) - (2x^2 + x - 4) \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Change the sign of every term in the second bracket: \\( +2x^2 \\to -2x^2 \\), \\( +x \\to -x \\), \\( -4 \\to +4 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. So it becomes \\( 5x^2 - 3x + 2 - 2x^2 - x + 4 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Combine like terms: \\( (5-2)x^2 + (-3-1)x + (2+4) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Result: \\[ 3x^2 - 4x + 6. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Notice the last term: \\( 2 - (-4) = 2 + 4 = 6 \\). Missing the double negative here is the most common slip.</p>", "check": {"question": "\\( (3x^2 - x + 2) - (x^2 + 4x - 5) = ? \\)", "options": ["\\( 2x^2 - 5x + 7 \\)", "\\( 2x^2 + 3x + 7 \\)", "\\( 2x^2 - 5x - 3 \\)", "\\( 4x^2 - 5x + 7 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Change every sign in the second bracket: \\( 3x^2 - x + 2 - x^2 - 4x + 5 = 2x^2 - 5x + 7 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you multiply polynomials?", "html": "<p>Multiply <strong>every</strong> term in the first bracket by every term in the second, then collect like terms. The degree of the product is the sum of the two degrees (a cubic times a quadratic gives degree \\( 3+2 = 5 \\)).</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( (x - 3)(x^2 + 2x - 1) \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( x \\times (x^2 + 2x - 1) = x^3 + 2x^2 - x \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( -3 \\times (x^2 + 2x - 1) = -3x^2 - 6x + 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Add the two rows, lining up like terms: \\( x^3 + (2-3)x^2 + (-1-6)x + 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Result: \\[ x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 3. \\]</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>A useful special case to recognise instantly is the <strong>difference of two squares</strong>: \\( (x+a)(x-a) = x^2 - a^2 \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "\\( (x - 5)(x + 2) = ? \\)", "options": ["\\( x^2 - 3x - 10 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 7x - 10 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 3x + 10 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 10 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x^2 + 2x - 5x - 10 = x^2 - 3x - 10 \\). The middle term comes from \\( 2x - 5x \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you divide polynomials by long division?", "html": "<p><strong>Polynomial (algebraic) long division</strong> works exactly like the long division of numbers. At each step you divide the leading terms, multiply back, and subtract to get a new, smaller polynomial. You stop when what is left has a <em>lower degree than the divisor</em> — that leftover is the <strong>remainder</strong>, and the terms you built up on top form the <strong>quotient</strong>.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — divide \\( x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 \\) by \\( x + 3 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( x^3 \\div x = x^2 \\). Multiply: \\( x^2(x+3) = x^3 + 3x^2 \\). Subtract: \\( (x^3 + 2x^2) - (x^3 + 3x^2) = -x^2 \\). Bring down \\( -5x \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( -x^2 \\div x = -x \\). Multiply: \\( -x(x+3) = -x^2 - 3x \\). Subtract: \\( (-x^2 - 5x) - (-x^2 - 3x) = -2x \\). Bring down \\( +8 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( -2x \\div x = -2 \\). Multiply: \\( -2(x+3) = -2x - 6 \\). Subtract: \\( (-2x + 8) - (-2x - 6) = 14 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Nothing is left to bring down and \\( 14 \\) has lower degree than \\( x+3 \\), so we stop.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the <strong>quotient is \\( x^2 - x - 2 \\)</strong> and the <strong>remainder is \\( 14 \\)</strong>. In one line: \\[ x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 = (x+3)(x^2 - x - 2) + 14. \\] Check by expanding the right-hand side — it returns the original. If a power is missing from the dividend (say no \\( x^2 \\) term), write it in as \\( 0x^2 \\) so your columns stay lined up.</p>", "check": {"question": "When \\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 \\) is divided by \\( x - 1 \\), what is the remainder?", "options": ["\\( 0 \\)", "\\( 6 \\)", "\\( -6 \\)", "\\( 2 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The division is exact: \\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 = (x-1)(2x^2 + x - 6) \\), so the remainder is \\( 0 \\) — which means \\( x - 1 \\) is a factor."}}, {"title": "How do you divide by equating coefficients instead?", "html": "<p>There is a neat alternative to the long-division layout: write down the answer in the form <em>dividend</em> \\( = \\) (<em>divisor</em>)(<em>quotient</em>) \\( + \\) <em>remainder</em> with unknown letters, then <strong>equate coefficients</strong> to pin the letters down. For a cubic divided by a linear divisor the quotient is a quadratic \\( x^2 + bx + c \\) and the remainder is a single number \\( d \\).</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — same division, \\( x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 \\) by \\( x + 3 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Write \\( x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 = (x+3)(x^2 + bx + c) + d \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Expand the right: \\( x^3 + (b+3)x^2 + (c+3b)x + (3c + d) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Compare \\( x^2 \\): \\( b + 3 = 2 \\Rightarrow b = -1 \\). Compare \\( x \\): \\( c + 3b = -5 \\Rightarrow c = -2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Compare constants: \\( 3c + d = 8 \\Rightarrow -6 + d = 8 \\Rightarrow d = 14 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>This gives quotient \\( x^2 - x - 2 \\) and remainder \\( 14 \\) — exactly as long division did. Use whichever method you prefer, but be ready to <strong>use long division when a question specifically asks for it</strong>.</p>", "check": {"question": "In \\( x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 = (x+3)(x^2 + bx + c) + d \\), what is \\( b \\)?", "options": ["\\( -1 \\)", "\\( 2 \\)", "\\( -2 \\)", "\\( 1 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Comparing the \\( x^2 \\) coefficients: \\( b + 3 = 2 \\), so \\( b = -1 \\)."}}, {"title": "How should you state the quotient and the remainder?", "html": "<p>This is the mark that examiners report is most often thrown away. After a correct division you must <strong>state the quotient AND the remainder, both clearly labelled</strong>. Two traps to avoid:</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Not identifying the quotient.</strong> Doing the working but never writing \"Quotient = …\" leaves the final mark unearned. If the answer box says <em>Quotient =</em> and <em>Remainder =</em>, fill in both.</li>\n              <li><strong>Giving the remainder as a fraction.</strong> The remainder is a <em>number</em> (more generally, a polynomial of lower degree than the divisor). Dividing \\( x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 \\) by \\( x+3 \\) can be written \\[ x^2 - x - 2 + \\frac{14}{x+3}, \\] but the <strong>remainder is \\( 14 \\)</strong>, not \\( \\frac{14}{x+3} \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>A remainder of \\( 0 \\) is special: it means the divisor is a <strong>factor</strong>, which links straight to the factor theorem in the next lesson.</p>", "check": {"question": "The remainder when a cubic is divided by \\( x - a \\) is always:", "options": ["a constant (a single number)", "a linear expression in \\( x \\)", "a fraction with \\( x - a \\) on the bottom", "equal to zero"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The remainder must have lower degree than the divisor \\( x - a \\) (degree 1), so it is a degree-0 constant. It is only ever \\( 0 \\) when \\( x - a \\) is a factor."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Polynomial", "definition": "A sum of terms \\( a x^n \\) with whole-number powers \\( n \\)."}, {"term": "Degree", "definition": "The highest power of the variable in the polynomial."}, {"term": "Coefficient", "definition": "The number multiplying a power of \\( x \\)."}, {"term": "Constant term", "definition": "The term with no \\( x \\) (power \\( 0 \\))."}, {"term": "Like terms", "definition": "Terms with the same power of \\( x \\); only these can be combined."}, {"term": "Descending order", "definition": "Writing a polynomial from the highest power down."}, {"term": "Dividend", "definition": "The polynomial being divided."}, {"term": "Divisor", "definition": "The polynomial you divide by."}, {"term": "Quotient", "definition": "The result of a division, before the remainder."}, {"term": "Remainder", "definition": "What is left over; lower degree than the divisor (a number for a linear divisor)."}, {"term": "Long division", "definition": "Divide leading terms, multiply back, subtract, repeat."}, {"term": "Equating coefficients", "definition": "Write dividend = (divisor)(quotient) + remainder and match coefficients."}, {"term": "Difference of two squares", "definition": "\\( (x+a)(x-a) = x^2 - a^2 \\)."}, {"term": "Placeholder term", "definition": "A \\( 0x^n \\) written in for a missing power to keep columns aligned."}, {"term": "Factor (remainder 0)", "definition": "If \\( x - a \\) divides exactly, it is a factor of the polynomial."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "Add: \\( (3x^2 + 2x - 5) + (x^2 - 4x + 1) \\).", "options": ["\\( 4x^2 - 2x - 4 \\)", "\\( 4x^2 + 6x - 4 \\)", "\\( 4x^2 - 2x - 5 \\)", "\\( 4x^4 - 2x - 4 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Collect like terms: \\( (3+1)x^2 + (2-4)x + (-5+1) = 4x^2 - 2x - 4 \\). Powers are not added when combining terms."}, {"question": "Subtract: \\( (5x^2 - 3x + 2) - (2x^2 + x - 4) \\).", "options": ["\\( 3x^2 - 4x + 6 \\)", "\\( 3x^2 - 4x - 2 \\)", "\\( 3x^2 - 2x - 2 \\)", "\\( 3x^2 - 2x + 6 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Change every sign in the second bracket: \\( 5x^2 - 3x + 2 - 2x^2 - x + 4 = 3x^2 - 4x + 6 \\). Note \\( 2 - (-4) = 6 \\)."}, {"question": "Expand: \\( (x + 4)(x - 2) \\).", "options": ["\\( x^2 + 2x - 8 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 6x - 8 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 8 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 2x + 8 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x^2 - 2x + 4x - 8 = x^2 + 2x - 8 \\). The middle term is \\( -2x + 4x = 2x \\)."}, {"question": "Expand: \\( (x - 3)(x^2 + 2x - 1) \\).", "options": ["\\( x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 3 \\)", "\\( x^3 + 5x^2 - 7x + 3 \\)", "\\( x^3 - x^2 - 7x - 3 \\)", "\\( x^3 - x^2 + 5x + 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x(x^2+2x-1) = x^3+2x^2-x \\) and \\( -3(x^2+2x-1) = -3x^2-6x+3 \\); adding gives \\( x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 3 \\)."}, {"question": "What is the degree of the product \\( (2x^3 - 5)(x^2 + x) \\)?", "options": ["5", "6", "3", "2"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The degree of a product is the sum of the degrees: \\( 3 + 2 = 5 \\)."}, {"question": "Divide \\( x^3 - 3x^2 - x - 3 \\) by \\( x - 3 \\). What is the quotient?", "options": ["\\( x^2 - 1 \\)", "\\( x^2 - x - 4 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 6 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 1 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "After the first step the working has no \\( x^2 \\) term left, so the quotient''s \\( x \\) coefficient is \\( 0 \\): quotient \\( = x^2 - 1 \\), remainder \\( -6 \\). Check: \\( (x-3)(x^2-1) - 6 = x^3 - 3x^2 - x - 3 \\)."}, {"question": "Dividing \\( x^3 - 3x^2 - x - 3 \\) by \\( x - 3 \\) leaves what remainder?", "options": ["\\( -6 \\)", "\\( 6 \\)", "\\( \\frac{-6}{x-3} \\)", "\\( 0 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The remainder is the constant left at the end, \\( -6 \\). \\( \\frac{-6}{x-3} \\) is the fractional part of the full answer, not the remainder."}, {"question": "When you divide \\( x^3 + 4x^2 + x + 2 \\) by \\( x + 2 \\), what is the first term of the quotient?", "options": ["\\( x^2 \\)", "\\( x^3 \\)", "\\( x \\)", "\\( 2x^2 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Divide the leading terms: \\( x^3 \\div x = x^2 \\). That is always the first step of polynomial long division."}, {"question": "A polynomial is divided by \\( x - a \\) and the remainder is \\( 0 \\). What does this tell you?", "options": ["\\( x - a \\) is a factor of the polynomial", "The polynomial is linear", "The quotient is also \\( 0 \\)", "You made an arithmetic mistake"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A remainder of \\( 0 \\) means the division is exact, so \\( x - a \\) divides the polynomial exactly — it is a factor."}, {"question": "It is given that \\( x^3 + 4x^2 + x - 6 = (x + 2)(x^2 + ax + b) \\). Find \\( a \\).", "options": ["\\( 2 \\)", "\\( 4 \\)", "\\( -2 \\)", "\\( 6 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Comparing \\( x^2 \\) terms in the expansion \\( (x+2)(x^2+ax+b) = x^3 + (a+2)x^2 + \\dots \\): \\( a + 2 = 4 \\Rightarrow a = 2 \\) (the quotient is \\( x^2 + 2x - 3 \\))."}, {"question": "To divide \\( 2x^3 - 5x + 1 \\) by \\( x - 1 \\), what should you do about the missing \\( x^2 \\) term?", "options": ["Write it in as \\( 0x^2 \\) to keep the columns lined up", "Ignore it — a missing term has no effect", "Add it to the constant term", "Move the \\( -5x \\) up into its place"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Insert a \\( 0x^2 \\) placeholder so every power has a column; otherwise the subtractions misalign and errors creep in."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "A polynomial written with its powers going from highest to lowest is in [descending] order."}, {"text": "The [degree] of a polynomial is the highest power of the variable, and the number multiplying a power of \\( x \\) is its [coefficient]."}, {"text": "To subtract one polynomial from another you must change the [sign] of every term in the second bracket."}, {"text": "In long division the expression built up on top is the [quotient] and the value left over at the end is the [remainder]."}, {"text": "When \\( x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 \\) is divided by \\( x + 3 \\), the quotient is \\( x^2 - x - 2 \\) and the remainder is [14]."}, {"text": "When a polynomial is divided by \\( x - a \\) and the remainder is [zero], then \\( x - a \\) is a factor."}, {"text": "When dividing, insert a [placeholder] (a term with coefficient 0) for any missing power so the columns stay lined up."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "The degree of a polynomial is the highest power of its variable.", "answer": true, "explain": "Correct — e.g. \\( 4x^5 - 2x^2 + 7 \\) has degree \\( 5 \\)."}, {"statement": "\\( (x + 2)(x - 2) = x^2 - 4 \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "This is the difference of two squares: \\( (x+a)(x-a) = x^2 - a^2 \\), here \\( a = 2 \\)."}, {"statement": "When subtracting polynomials you only change the sign of the first term of the second bracket.", "answer": false, "explain": "You must change the sign of EVERY term in the second bracket, not just the first."}, {"statement": "The remainder from a polynomial division can be written as a fraction and still counts as the remainder.", "answer": false, "explain": "The remainder is a number (of lower degree than the divisor). \\( \\frac{14}{x+3} \\) is the fractional part of the answer, not the remainder \\( 14 \\)."}, {"statement": "In \\( x^3 + 2x^2 - 5x + 8 = (x + 3)(x^2 - x - 2) + 14 \\), the number \\( 14 \\) is the remainder.", "answer": true, "explain": "Written as (divisor)(quotient) + remainder, the constant \\( 14 \\) is exactly the remainder."}, {"statement": "Dividing a degree-3 polynomial by a degree-1 polynomial gives a quotient of degree 2.", "answer": true, "explain": "Degrees subtract: \\( 3 - 1 = 2 \\), so the quotient is a quadratic."}, {"statement": "If a polynomial divides by \\( x - a \\) with remainder \\( 0 \\), then \\( x - a \\) is a factor.", "answer": true, "explain": "Remainder \\( 0 \\) means the division is exact, which is the definition of a factor."}, {"statement": "Adding \\( x^2 \\) and \\( x^3 \\) gives \\( x^5 \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "They are unlike terms, so they stay as \\( x^3 + x^2 \\). You only add indices when you MULTIPLY: \\( x^2 \\times x^3 = x^5 \\)."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "\\( (4x^2 - 2x + 3) - (x^2 - 5x + 1) = 3x^2 - 7x + 2 \\)", "truth": "The minus applies to EVERY term in the second bracket. A weak answer only negates the first term; a strong answer writes \\( 4x^2 - 2x + 3 - x^2 + 5x - 1 = 3x^2 + 3x + 2 \\).", "check": {"question": "\\( (4x^2 - 2x + 3) - (x^2 - 5x + 1) = ? \\)", "options": ["\\( 3x^2 + 3x + 2 \\)", "\\( 3x^2 - 7x + 2 \\)", "\\( 3x^2 + 3x + 4 \\)", "\\( 3x^2 - 7x + 4 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Negate all three: \\( -x^2 + 5x - 1 \\), then collect: \\( 3x^2 + 3x + 2 \\)."}}, {"myth": "The remainder when \\( x^3 - 3x^2 - x - 3 \\) is divided by \\( x - 3 \\) is \\( \\frac{-6}{x-3} \\)", "truth": "The remainder is the constant \\( -6 \\). A weak answer leaves it as a fraction; a strong answer states ''Remainder \\( = -6 \\)''. The \\( \\frac{-6}{x-3} \\) is only the fractional part of the full quotient-plus-fraction form.", "check": {"question": "What is the remainder here?", "options": ["\\( -6 \\)", "\\( \\frac{-6}{x-3} \\)", "\\( 6 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 1 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A remainder is a number of lower degree than the divisor — here \\( -6 \\)."}}, {"myth": "Doing the long division correctly but writing no ''Quotient ='' or ''Remainder ='' answer", "truth": "The final mark is for IDENTIFYING both results. A weak answer stops after the working; a strong answer states the quotient AND the remainder explicitly, filling in both answer lines.", "check": {"question": "After a correct division you must always:", "options": ["State the quotient AND the remainder clearly", "State only the quotient", "State only the remainder", "Leave the examiner to read your working"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The 2023 examiners noted many lost the last mark by not identifying the quotient (or by giving the remainder as a fraction)."}}, {"myth": "Dividing \\( 2x^3 - 5x + 1 \\) by \\( x - 1 \\) without a place for the missing \\( x^2 \\) term", "truth": "Insert a \\( 0x^2 \\) placeholder. A weak answer mis-aligns the columns and makes subtraction slips; a strong answer writes \\( 2x^3 + 0x^2 - 5x + 1 \\) so every power lines up.", "check": {"question": "How do you handle a missing \\( x^2 \\) term in the dividend?", "options": ["Write it as \\( 0x^2 \\) to keep columns aligned", "Skip that column entirely", "Add it to the \\( -5x \\)", "Move the constant up"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A \\( 0x^2 \\) placeholder keeps the long-division columns aligned."}}, {"myth": "\\( x^2 + x^3 = x^5 \\)", "truth": "These are unlike terms and cannot be combined; the answer is just \\( x^3 + x^2 \\). A weak answer adds the indices; a strong answer only adds indices when MULTIPLYING, e.g. \\( x^2 \\times x^3 = x^5 \\).", "check": {"question": "Simplify \\( x^2 + x^3 \\).", "options": ["\\( x^3 + x^2 \\)", "\\( x^5 \\)", "\\( 2x^5 \\)", "\\( x^6 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Unlike terms stay separate; indices add only under multiplication."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "State the quotient AND the remainder", "html": "<p>The 2023 examiners reported that candidates who divided correctly still lost the final mark by <strong>not identifying the quotient</strong>, or by <strong>giving the remainder as a fraction</strong>.</p><p><strong>0 marks lost:</strong> a page of correct working but no stated answer, or \"remainder \\( = \\frac{-6}{x-3} \\)\".</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> \"Quotient \\( = x^2 + 2x + 3 \\), Remainder \\( = -6 \\)\" — both labelled, the remainder a number.</p>", "check": {"question": "How do you secure the final mark on a long-division question?", "options": ["Label both the quotient and the remainder (a number)", "Show working only", "Give the remainder as a fraction", "Give only the quotient"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Both results must be stated, and the remainder must be a number, not a fraction."}}, {"title": "Show every step (method marks)", "html": "<p>On a \"use long division\" question the method mark (M1) needs your working to be <strong>visible</strong>: the \\( x^2 \\) term of the quotient and the \\( x^3 + x^2 \\) line of the multiplication must be seen. Write each subtraction on its own line so a single slip costs one mark, not all three.</p>", "check": {"question": "Why write out each subtraction line in long division?", "options": ["So the method mark is earned even if a later step slips", "To use more paper", "It is optional decoration", "To avoid using a calculator"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Visible correct steps earn the M mark independently of the final answer."}}, {"title": "''Use long division'' means show that method", "html": "<p>If a question says <em>\"use long division\"</em>, the equate-coefficients shortcut may not earn the method mark even with the right answer. Match the method the command word names. When no method is specified, use whichever you are faster and safer with.</p>", "check": {"question": "A question says ''use long division''. You should:", "options": ["Carry out and show the long-division method", "Use equating coefficients instead", "Just write the answer", "Use a calculator to factorise"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Follow the named method so the method marks are available to you."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "<p>Use long division to find the quotient and the remainder when \\( x^3 + 3x^2 + 5x - 3 \\) is divided by \\( x + 1 \\).</p>", "marks": 3, "hint": "Divide term by term; the remainder is the constant left at the end. State the quotient and the remainder separately, and do not leave the remainder as a fraction.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 3 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — sight of the correct process: the \\( x^2 \\) term in the quotient and the \\( x^3 + x^2 \\) line in the working must be seen.</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — fully correct division (working correct down to the remainder).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — remainder and quotient correctly identified: Quotient \\( = x^2 + 2x + 3 \\), Remainder \\( = -6 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>The three marks are for starting the division correctly, completing it without error, and then clearly stating both the quotient and the remainder.</li>\n              <li>The remainder must be given as the number \\( -6 \\), not as \\( \\frac{-6}{x+1} \\). (N.B. the answer may be written at the bottom of the working.)</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Candidates who used the traditional long-division technique were generally successful, but a significant proportion then did not identify the quotient, while others gave the remainder as a fraction.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths', '2-2-the-factor-theorem-and-cubics', '2.2 The Factor Theorem and Cubics', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "What is the factor theorem?", "html": "<p>The <strong>factor theorem</strong> connects a <em>value</em> of a polynomial to one of its <em>factors</em>. For a polynomial \\( \\text{f}(x) \\):</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>If \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\), then \\( (x - a) \\) is a <strong>factor</strong> of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\).</li>\n              <li>The reverse is also true: if \\( (x - a) \\) is a factor, then \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\).</li>\n              <li>For a factor of the form \\( (bx - a) \\), test \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{a}{b}\\right) \\): if it is zero, \\( (bx - a) \\) is a factor. (Set \\( bx - a = 0 \\) to see why: \\( x = \\tfrac{a}{b} \\).)</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Watch the <strong>sign</strong>: the factor \\( (x - a) \\) matches the value \\( x = a \\), so \\( (x + 3) \\) is a factor exactly when \\( \\text{f}(-3) = 0 \\).</p>\n            <p><strong>Spec boundary:</strong> the factor theorem is the special case of the <em>remainder theorem</em> where the remainder is zero — but the <strong>remainder theorem was removed from this specification in 2018</strong>, so you are only ever tested on the factor theorem.</p>", "check": {"question": "If \\( \\text{f}(3) = 0 \\), which is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\)?", "options": ["\\( (x+3) \\)", "\\( (x-3) \\)", "\\( 3x \\)", "\\( (x-\\tfrac{1}{3}) \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) gives the factor \\( (x-a) \\); here \\( a=3 \\), so \\( (x-3) \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you find a linear factor of a cubic?", "html": "<p>A cubic will not always factorise by inspection, so you hunt for a first factor with the factor theorem. The trick is knowing <strong>which values to try</strong>.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>Any whole-number root must be a <strong>divisor of the constant term</strong>. For \\( x^3 - 5x^2 + 2x + 8 \\) the constant is \\( 8 \\), so test \\( x = \\pm 1,\\ \\pm 2,\\ \\pm 4,\\ \\pm 8 \\).</li>\n              <li>Substitute each candidate into \\( \\text{f}(x) \\). The moment you get \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\), you have found the factor \\( (x - a) \\) — stop testing.</li>\n              <li>If the leading coefficient is not \\( 1 \\), also try <strong>fractions</strong> \\( \\dfrac{\\text{divisor of the constant}}{\\text{divisor of the leading coefficient}} \\) (see the \\( (bx-a) \\) card).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Start with the small, tidy values \\( \\pm 1, \\pm 2 \\) — examiners design these questions so a low divisor works.</p>", "check": {"question": "For \\( \\text{f}(x)=x^3-2x^2-5x+6 \\), which set should you test first?", "options": ["Divisors of 6: \\( \\pm1,\\pm2,\\pm3,\\pm6 \\)", "Only \\( 1 \\) and \\( 2 \\)", "Divisors of 2", "Multiples of 6"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Whole-number roots divide the constant term, which is 6, so try \\( \\pm1,\\pm2,\\pm3,\\pm6 \\)."}}, {"title": "Worked example: factorise and solve a cubic", "html": "<p><strong>Solve \\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 = 0 \\).</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Constant term is \\( 6 \\); try small divisors. \\( \\text{f}(1) = 2 - 1 - 7 + 6 = 0 \\), so \\( (x - 1) \\) is a factor.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Divide (or equate coefficients) to get the quadratic factor: \\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 = (x - 1)(2x^2 + x - 6) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Factorise the quadratic: \\( 2x^2 + x - 6 = (2x - 3)(x + 2) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. So \\[ 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 = (x - 1)(2x - 3)(x + 2). \\]</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. <strong>Solve:</strong> set each factor to \\( 0 \\): \\( x = 1,\\ x = \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ x = -2 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Check one root: \\( \\text{f}(-2) = 2(-8) - 4 + 14 + 6 = 0 \\). ✓ Finding the factors is only <em>half</em> the job — the question said \"solve\", so you must give the three \\( x \\)-values.</p>", "check": {"question": "The solutions of \\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 = 0 \\) are:", "options": ["\\( x=1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\)", "\\( x=-1,\\ -\\tfrac{3}{2},\\ 2 \\)", "\\( x=1,\\ 2,\\ 3 \\)", "\\( x=1,\\ -2 \\) only"], "answer": 0, "explain": "From \\( (x-1)(2x-3)(x+2)=0 \\): \\( x=1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\) — all three roots."}}, {"title": "How do you test for a factor like (2x − 3)?", "html": "<p>When the leading coefficient is not \\( 1 \\), some factors are <strong>non-monic</strong>, such as \\( (2x - 3) \\). To test one, use the \\( (bx - a) \\) rule: evaluate \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{a}{b}\\right) \\).</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>\\( (2x - 3) \\) is a factor when \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{3}{2}\\right) = 0 \\), because \\( 2x - 3 = 0 \\Rightarrow x = \\tfrac{3}{2} \\).</li>\n              <li>\\( (3x + 1) \\) is a factor when \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{1}{3}\\right) = 0 \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Check for the last worked example:</strong> \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{3}{2}\\right) = 2\\left(\\tfrac{27}{8}\\right) - \\tfrac{9}{4} - \\tfrac{21}{2} + 6 = 0 \\), confirming \\( (2x - 3) \\) is a factor.</p>\n            <p>In practice you rarely need this on a cubic — one whole-number factor usually appears first, and then a quadratic (which you factorise normally) takes care of the non-monic factor.</p>", "check": {"question": "To test whether \\( (3x - 2) \\) is a factor, evaluate:", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(\\tfrac{3}{2}) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(\\tfrac{2}{3}) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-\\tfrac{2}{3}) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(3) \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( 3x-2=0 \\Rightarrow x=\\tfrac{2}{3} \\), so test \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{2}{3}\\right) \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you find the quadratic factor?", "html": "<p>Once you have one linear factor \\( (x - a) \\), the cubic is \\( (x - a) \\times (\\text{a quadratic}) \\). Two reliable ways to find that quadratic:</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Algebraic long division</strong> — divide the cubic by \\( (x - a) \\); the quotient is the quadratic (covered in lesson 2.1).</li>\n              <li><strong>Equating coefficients</strong> — write \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x - a)(px^2 + qx + r) \\), expand, and match the coefficients of each power of \\( x \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — \\( x^3 - x^2 - 4x + 4 \\), given \\( (x - 1) \\) is a factor:</strong> write \\( (x - 1)(x^2 + bx - 4) \\). The constant \\( -1 \\times (-4) = 4 \\) ✓. Matching the \\( x^2 \\) term: \\( b - 1 = -1 \\Rightarrow b = 0 \\). So \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x - 1)(x^2 - 4) = (x - 1)(x - 2)(x + 2) \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "\\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 = (x - 1)(2x^2 + bx - 6) \\). What is \\( b \\)?", "options": ["\\( b = 1 \\)", "\\( b = -1 \\)", "\\( b = 2 \\)", "\\( b = -6 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Matching the \\( x^2 \\) coefficient: \\( b - 2 = -1 \\Rightarrow b = 1 \\); the \\( x \\) term \\( -6 - b = -7 \\) confirms \\( b = 1 \\)."}}, {"title": "What does ''detailed reasoning'' demand here?", "html": "<p>Factor-theorem cubics are a favourite <strong>\"detailed reasoning\" (DR)</strong> question. The DR instruction means <em>every analytical step must be visible</em> — a calculator may be used, but an answer read straight off it earns nothing.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>You must <strong>show \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\)</strong> for your trial value — this proves you used the factor theorem.</li>\n              <li>You must then <strong>obtain the quadratic factor</strong> before stating the three linear factors (or apply the factor theorem to at least two values).</li>\n              <li>Writing the factorisation \\( (x + 1)(x - 2)(x - 4) \\) with <em>no working</em> scores <strong>zero</strong> on a DR question, even if it is correct.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>And remember: a factorised cubic is <strong>not yet solved</strong>. \"Solve \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\)\" needs each factor set to zero and the \\( x \\)-values written down.</p>", "check": {"question": "In a DR factor-theorem question, what must be visible?", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) for a trial value, and the quadratic factor", "only the three final factors", "just the calculator answer", "the value of the discriminant"], "answer": 0, "explain": "DR requires the factor-theorem step \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) to be shown and the quadratic factor obtained."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Factor theorem", "definition": "If \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\) then \\( (x - a) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\)."}, {"term": "Converse", "definition": "If \\( (x - a) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\), then \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\)."}, {"term": "Testing \\( (bx - a) \\)", "definition": "\\( (bx - a) \\) is a factor when \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{a}{b}\\right) = 0 \\)."}, {"term": "Finding a first factor", "definition": "Test the divisors of the constant term until \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\)."}, {"term": "Remainder theorem", "definition": "Not on the 6993 specification — use the factor theorem only."}, {"term": "Quadratic factor", "definition": "After one linear factor, divide (or equate coefficients) to get the quadratic."}, {"term": "Equating coefficients", "definition": "Write \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x - a)(\\text{quadratic}) \\) and match coefficients."}, {"term": "Solving a cubic", "definition": "Factorise fully, then set each factor equal to zero."}, {"term": "Repeated root", "definition": "A squared factor such as \\( (x + 1)^2 \\) gives one root value twice."}, {"term": "Candidate roots (leading coeff 1)", "definition": "The \\( \\pm \\) divisors of the constant term."}, {"term": "Candidate roots (leading coeff ≠ 1)", "definition": "\\( \\pm\\dfrac{\\text{divisor of constant}}{\\text{divisor of leading coefficient}} \\)."}, {"term": "Detailed reasoning", "definition": "Every step seen; \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) shown; calculator-only answer scores 0."}, {"term": "\\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 \\)", "definition": "\\( (x-1)(2x-3)(x+2) \\); roots \\( 1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\)."}, {"term": "Number of roots of a cubic", "definition": "Up to three; a repeated factor counts a root more than once."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "If \\( (x - 4) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\), then:", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(0) = 4 \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(4) = 0 \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-4) = 0 \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(4) = 4 \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The factor \\( (x-a) \\) means \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\); here \\( a=4 \\), so \\( \\text{f}(4)=0 \\)."}, {"question": "Which condition shows that \\( (x + 2) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\)?", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(2) = 0 \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(0) = -2 \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-2) = 0 \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(2) = -2 \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "\\( (x+2)=(x-(-2)) \\), so the matching value is \\( x=-2 \\): \\( \\text{f}(-2)=0 \\)."}, {"question": "For \\( \\text{f}(x) = x^3 - 5x^2 + 2x + 8 \\), what is \\( \\text{f}(2) \\)?", "options": ["\\( 16 \\)", "\\( -4 \\)", "\\( 8 \\)", "\\( 0 \\)"], "answer": 3, "explain": "\\( \\text{f}(2) = 8 - 20 + 4 + 8 = 0 \\), so \\( (x-2) \\) is a factor."}, {"question": "For \\( \\text{f}(x) = x^3 - x^2 - 4x + 4 \\), which is a factor?", "options": ["\\( (x - 1) \\)", "\\( (x + 1) \\)", "\\( (x - 4) \\)", "\\( (x + 4) \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( \\text{f}(1) = 1 - 1 - 4 + 4 = 0 \\), so \\( (x-1) \\) is a factor. \\( \\text{f}(-1)=6\\ne 0 \\)."}, {"question": "To test whether \\( (2x + 1) \\) is a factor, evaluate:", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(\\tfrac{1}{2}) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-\\tfrac{1}{2}) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(2) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-2) \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( 2x+1=0 \\Rightarrow x=-\\tfrac{1}{2} \\), so test \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(-\\tfrac{1}{2}\\right) \\)."}, {"question": "\\( \\text{f}(x) = (x - 1)(x + 2)(2x - 3) \\). The solutions of \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\) are:", "options": ["\\( x = -1,\\ 2,\\ -\\tfrac{3}{2} \\)", "\\( x = 1,\\ -2 \\) only", "\\( x = 1,\\ -2,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2} \\)", "the factorised form is the solution"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Set each factor to 0: \\( x=1 \\), \\( x=-2 \\), \\( x=\\tfrac{3}{2} \\)."}, {"question": "A student writes \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x - 1)(2x^2 + x - 6) \\) and stops. To solve \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\) they must next:", "options": ["factorise the quadratic and set each factor to 0", "divide again by \\( (x - 1) \\)", "substitute \\( x = 0 \\)", "state the remainder"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Factorise \\( 2x^2+x-6=(2x-3)(x+2) \\), then set every factor to zero."}, {"question": "\\( x^3 - 3x - 2 \\) has root \\( x = 2 \\); dividing by \\( (x - 2) \\) gives \\( x^2 + 2x + 1 \\). The other roots are:", "options": ["\\( x = 1 \\) and \\( x = -2 \\)", "\\( x = -1 \\) (repeated)", "\\( x = 2 \\) (repeated)", "\\( x = 1 \\) only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( x^2+2x+1=(x+1)^2=0 \\Rightarrow x=-1 \\), a repeated root."}, {"question": "For \\( \\text{f}(x) = x^3 + 4x^2 + x - 6 \\), which value is NOT worth testing with the factor theorem?", "options": ["\\( x = 1 \\)", "\\( x = -2 \\)", "\\( x = 5 \\)", "\\( x = 3 \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Whole-number roots divide the constant \\( 6 \\): \\( \\pm1,\\pm2,\\pm3,\\pm6 \\). \\( 5 \\) is not a divisor of 6."}, {"question": "If \\( \\text{f}(a) = 7 \\), what can you conclude?", "options": ["\\( (x - a) \\) is a factor", "\\( (x - a) \\) is not a factor", "the remainder theorem gives the roots", "\\( a \\) is a root"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The factor theorem needs \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\); since \\( \\text{f}(a)=7\\ne 0 \\), \\( (x-a) \\) is not a factor."}, {"question": "For \\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 \\), the value of \\( \\text{f}(1) \\) is:", "options": ["\\( 2 \\)", "\\( 6 \\)", "\\( 0 \\)", "\\( -1 \\)"], "answer": 2, "explain": "\\( \\text{f}(1) = 2 - 1 - 7 + 6 = 0 \\), so \\( (x-1) \\) is a factor."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "The factor theorem states that if \\( \\text{f}(a) \\) equals [0], then \\( (x - a) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\)."}, {"text": "If \\( (x - 4) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\), then \\( \\text{f}(4) \\) equals [0]."}, {"text": "To find a whole-number factor of a cubic, test the [factors] of the constant term."}, {"text": "To test whether \\( (2x - 1) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\), work out f of [1/2]."}, {"text": "The factor theorem finds [linear] factors of a polynomial; the remainder theorem is [not] on this specification."}, {"text": "After factorising, you solve \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\) by setting each [factor] equal to zero."}, {"text": "For \\( 2x^3 - x^2 - 7x + 6 \\), testing gives \\( \\text{f}(1) = 0 \\), so (x − [1]) is a factor."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "If \\( \\text{f}(5) = 0 \\), then \\( (x - 5) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "This is exactly the factor theorem: \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\Rightarrow (x-a) \\) is a factor."}, {"statement": "If \\( (x + 3) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\), then \\( \\text{f}(3) = 0 \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "The factor \\( (x+3)=(x-(-3)) \\) matches \\( x=-3 \\), so it is \\( \\text{f}(-3)=0 \\), not \\( \\text{f}(3) \\)."}, {"statement": "The remainder theorem is examined on this qualification.", "answer": false, "explain": "The remainder theorem was removed from the 6993 specification in 2018; only the factor theorem is tested."}, {"statement": "To test whether \\( (3x - 1) \\) is a factor, you evaluate \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{1}{3}\\right) \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "\\( 3x-1=0 \\Rightarrow x=\\tfrac{1}{3} \\), so \\( (3x-1) \\) is a factor when \\( \\text{f}\\!\\left(\\tfrac{1}{3}\\right)=0 \\)."}, {"statement": "A cubic can have a repeated root, so its ''three roots'' may include the same value more than once.", "answer": true, "explain": "A squared factor like \\( (x+1)^2 \\) contributes the root \\( x=-1 \\) twice, e.g. \\( x^3-3x-2=(x-2)(x+1)^2 \\)."}, {"statement": "Once you write \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x-1)(x+2)(2x-3) \\), you have solved \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "Factorising is not solving. You must set each factor to zero: \\( x=1,\\ -2,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2} \\)."}, {"statement": "In a ''detailed reasoning'' factor-theorem question, writing the three factors from your calculator with no working scores full marks.", "answer": false, "explain": "Answer-only responses score zero on a DR question; you must show \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) and obtain the quadratic factor."}, {"statement": "If \\( \\text{f}(2) = 3 \\), then \\( (x - 2) \\) is a factor of \\( \\text{f}(x) \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "\\( (x-2) \\) is a factor only when \\( \\text{f}(2)=0 \\); here \\( \\text{f}(2)=3 \\), so it is not a factor."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "To check the factor \\( (x - 2) \\), a student evaluates \\( \\text{f}(-2) \\).", "truth": "\\( (x - a) \\) is a factor when \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\), so \\( (x-2) \\) needs \\( \\text{f}(2) \\), not \\( \\text{f}(-2) \\). The value you substitute is the OPPOSITE sign to the number in the bracket.", "check": {"question": "\\( (x - 2) \\) is a factor. Which must be zero?", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(2) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-2) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(0) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(\\tfrac{1}{2}) \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( (x-2) \\) matches \\( x=2 \\), so \\( \\text{f}(2)=0 \\)."}}, {"myth": "Writing \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x-1)(2x-3)(x+2) \\) and stopping when asked to SOLVE \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\).", "truth": "Factorising is not solving. A weak answer leaves the brackets; a strong answer sets each factor to zero to give \\( x = 1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\).", "check": {"question": "Solve \\( (x-1)(2x-3)(x+2) = 0 \\).", "options": ["\\( x = 1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\)", "\\( x = 1,\\ 3,\\ 2 \\)", "\\( x = -1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ 2 \\)", "leave as factors"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Each factor set to zero gives \\( x=1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\)."}}, {"myth": "On a ''detailed reasoning'' question, quoting the three factors straight from a calculator.", "truth": "DR needs the method seen: show \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) and obtain the quadratic factor. A weak answer gives factors only (0 marks); a strong answer shows every step.", "check": {"question": "A DR factor-theorem answer with no working scores:", "options": ["full marks", "zero", "one mark", "half marks"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Answer-only DR responses score zero, even when the factorisation is correct."}}, {"myth": "Using successive factor-theorem trials and stopping at the first factor found, \\( x = -1 \\).", "truth": "A cubic has three roots. After one factor, find the quadratic factor to catch the rest — including a REPEATED root. For \\( x^3-3x-2 \\), stopping at \\( x=-1 \\) misses that it is repeated.", "check": {"question": "\\( x^3 - 3x - 2 = 0 \\) has root \\( x = 2 \\). The other root(s):", "options": ["\\( x = -1 \\) (repeated)", "\\( x = -1 \\) only, ignore repeats", "\\( x = 1 \\)", "there are none"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x^3-3x-2=(x-2)(x+1)^2 \\), so \\( x=-1 \\) is a repeated root."}}, {"myth": "For a cubic with constant term 6, testing only \\( x = 1 \\) and \\( x = 2 \\).", "truth": "The whole-number candidates are ALL divisors of the constant term: \\( \\pm1, \\pm2, \\pm3, \\pm6 \\) (plus fractions like \\( \\pm\\tfrac{1}{2}, \\pm\\tfrac{3}{2} \\) if the leading coefficient is not 1).", "check": {"question": "For a cubic with constant term 6, test:", "options": ["\\( \\pm1, \\pm2, \\pm3, \\pm6 \\)", "\\( 1 \\) and \\( 2 \\) only", "even numbers only", "\\( \\pm6 \\) only"], "answer": 0, "explain": "All divisors of the constant term are candidates: \\( \\pm1, \\pm2, \\pm3, \\pm6 \\)."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "The ''detailed reasoning'' ladder", "html": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> writing \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x+1)(x-2)(x-4) \\) straight from the calculator with no working — even though it is correct.</p><p><strong>Partial:</strong> showing \\( \\text{f}(2) = 0 \\) (so \\( (x-2) \\) is a factor) but then jumping to the three factors.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> show \\( \\text{f}(2) = 0 \\), obtain the quadratic factor \\( (x^2 - 3x - 4) \\), factorise it, then state \\( (x-2)(x-4)(x+1) \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "On a DR factor question, the safest response:", "options": ["show \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) then find the quadratic factor", "write the factors from the calculator", "give decimals", "state the remainder"], "answer": 0, "explain": "DR rewards the full visible method: \\( \\text{f}(a)=0 \\) then the quadratic factor."}}, {"title": "The sign trap: (x − a) matches f(a)", "html": "<p>The number you substitute is the <strong>opposite sign</strong> to the one in the bracket. To test \\( (x + 5) \\), evaluate \\( \\text{f}(-5) \\); to test \\( (x - 5) \\), evaluate \\( \\text{f}(5) \\). Getting this backwards is the most common way to miss a factor entirely.</p>", "check": {"question": "To check \\( (x + 5) \\) is a factor, evaluate:", "options": ["\\( \\text{f}(5) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(-5) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(0) \\)", "\\( \\text{f}(\\tfrac{1}{5}) \\)"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\\( (x+5)=(x-(-5)) \\), so evaluate \\( \\text{f}(-5) \\)."}}, {"title": "Factorising is not solving", "html": "<p>If the command word is <strong>\"solve\"</strong>, the factorisation is only the halfway point. \\( (x-1)(2x-3)(x+2) \\) earns the factorising marks, but the final answer marks need the roots: set each factor to zero and write \\( x = 1,\\ \\tfrac{3}{2},\\ -2 \\). Don''t leave marks on the table by stopping early.</p>", "check": {"question": "You have factorised \\( \\text{f}(x) \\). To finish ''solve \\( \\text{f}(x)=0 \\)'':", "options": ["set each factor equal to zero", "stop — that is the answer", "expand the brackets again", "find \\( \\text{f}(0) \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Solving means setting every factor to zero to read off the roots."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "<p>Using the factor theorem, factorise \\( \\text{f}(x) \\).</p><p><em>(You must show detailed reasoning.)</em></p>", "marks": 4, "hint": "Try the divisors of 8 until \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\); you must SHOW that value equals zero, then find the quadratic factor.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO1/AO2)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — attempt to find a factor by any means (e.g. trialling divisors of 8).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — showing \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\) where \\( a = -1,\\ 2 \\) or \\( 4 \\) must be seen (this is the detailed-reasoning step).</li>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — obtain a quadratic factor and attempt to factorise it.</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x - 2)(x - 4)(x + 1) \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>\\( \\text{f}(2) = 8 - 20 + 4 + 8 = 0 \\), so \\( (x-2) \\) is a factor; dividing gives \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x-2)(x^2 - 3x - 4) = (x-2)(x-4)(x+1) \\).</li>\n              <li>Alternative for the last two marks: apply the factor theorem to a second value, e.g. \\( \\text{f}(4) = 0 \\), then complete with the third factor.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Candidates who only wrote \\( \\text{f}(x) = (x + 1)(x - 2)(x - 4) \\) with no working scored zero — this is a detailed-reasoning question, so \\( \\text{f}(a) = 0 \\) and the quadratic factor must be shown.</li>\n              <li>Using a calculator to spot the roots is fine, but you must then demonstrate the factor-theorem reasoning to earn the marks.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>Hence solve the equation \\( \\text{f}(x) = 0 \\).</p>", "marks": 1, "hint": "Use your factors from (a) — set each equal to zero.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — \\( x = -1,\\ 2,\\ 4 \\) (follow through their factors in (a)).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>Each factor of \\( (x-2)(x-4)(x+1) \\) set to zero gives \\( x = 2,\\ 4,\\ -1 \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Almost always well done by those who had managed to factorise the cubic in part (a).</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p><em>In this question you must show detailed reasoning.</em></p><p>The equation \\( x^3 - 3x + k = 0 \\), where \\( k \\) is a constant, has a root \\( x = 2 \\).</p><p>Find the numerical value(s) of the other roots of this equation.</p>", "marks": 5, "hint": "Substitute the known root to find \\( k \\), then divide the cubic by \\( (x - 2) \\) — don''t stop at the first extra root, a cubic has three.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 5 marks (AO1/AO2)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — substitute \\( x = 2 \\) into \\( x^3 - 3x + k \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — \\( k = -2 \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — attempt to solve by division (divide \\( x^3 - 3x - 2 \\) by \\( (x - 2) \\)).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — correct quadratic factor \\( x^2 + 2x + 1 \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — other root \\( x = -1 \\) (repeated).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>\\( \\text{f}(2) = 8 - 6 + k = 0 \\Rightarrow k = -2 \\), so \\( x^3 - 3x - 2 = (x - 2)(x^2 + 2x + 1) = (x - 2)(x + 1)^2 \\).</li>\n              <li>Alternative: begin the division immediately; the remainder being 0 gives \\( k + 2 = 0 \\).</li>\n              <li>Accept \\( -1 \\) written once provided the three factors of the cubic are seen.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Most substituted \\( x = 2 \\), found \\( k = -2 \\), divided to obtain the quadratic factor and deduced the repeated root \\( x = -1 \\).</li>\n              <li>Successive factor-theorem trials were not a complete method: a cubic has three roots, and candidates using that route stopped after finding \\( x = -1 \\) once, missing the repeated root.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths', '2-3-setting-up-and-solving-equations', '2.3 Setting Up and Solving Equations', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "How do you turn a worded problem into an equation?", "html": "<p><strong>Setting up an equation</strong> means translating a real situation into algebra you can solve. The same five-step routine works whether the equation turns out to be linear, quadratic or cubic.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. <strong>Define the unknown.</strong> Write \"Let \\( x \\) be …\" and include its <strong>units</strong> (cm, km/h, £).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. <strong>Translate</strong> each sentence into algebra — \"5 more than\" is \\( +5 \\), \"3 times\" is \\( 3x \\), \"product\" is a multiplication.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. <strong>Solve</strong> the equation using the right method for its degree.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. <strong>Interpret</strong> the solution back in the context, with units.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. <strong>Reject</strong> any solution that cannot occur (a negative length, a fractional number of people).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>The commonest lost marks are skipping step 1 (never saying what \\( x \\) is) and skipping steps 4–5 (leaving a bare number instead of a value in context).</p>", "check": {"question": "What should the very first line of a set-up-a-model answer do?", "options": ["Define the unknown and its units, e.g. ''Let \\( x \\) be the width in cm''", "Write down the final answer", "Draw a graph", "Multiply everything out"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Always define your variable first — it makes every later step (and every mark) unambiguous."}}, {"title": "How do you set up and solve a linear equation in context?", "html": "<p>A <strong>linear equation</strong> has the unknown only to the power 1. Translate the words, then rearrange.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> A taxi charges a £3 booking fee plus £2 for every mile. A journey costs £17. How many miles was it?</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Let \\( m \\) be the number of miles.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Cost = fee + rate × miles: \\( 3 + 2m = 17 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Subtract 3: \\( 2m = 14 \\); divide by 2: \\( m = 7 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. In context: the journey was <strong>7 miles</strong>.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Check: \\( 3 + 2(7) = 17 \\). ✓ Notice the answer is a <em>value with units</em>, not just \"7\".</p>", "check": {"question": "A plumber charges £40 plus £30 per hour. A bill is £160. Which equation finds the hours \\( h \\)?", "options": ["\\( 40 + 30h = 160 \\)", "\\( 40h + 30 = 160 \\)", "\\( 70h = 160 \\)", "\\( 40 + 30 + h = 160 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Fixed £40 plus £30 for each hour: \\( 40 + 30h = 160 \\), giving \\( h = 4 \\) hours."}}, {"title": "How do you set up and solve a quadratic in context?", "html": "<p>When two quantities <strong>multiply</strong> (an area, a product of numbers), the equation is usually a <strong>quadratic</strong>. Rearrange to \\( ax^2 + bx + c = 0 \\), solve, then keep only the physically valid root.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> A rectangle is 2 cm longer than it is wide. Its area is 48 cm². Find its dimensions.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Let the width be \\( x \\) cm; the length is \\( (x + 2) \\) cm.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Area: \\( x(x + 2) = 48 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Expand and rearrange: \\( x^2 + 2x - 48 = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Factorise: \\( (x + 8)(x - 6) = 0 \\), so \\( x = -8 \\) or \\( x = 6 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. A width cannot be negative, so <strong>reject \\( x = -8 \\)</strong>.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the width is <strong>6 cm</strong> and the length is <strong>8 cm</strong>. Check: \\( 6 \\times 8 = 48 \\). ✓ Stating why you reject \\( x = -8 \\) is part of the answer.</p>", "check": {"question": "A quadratic modelling a length gives roots \\( x = 5 \\) and \\( x = -9 \\). The length is:", "options": ["\\( 5 \\) (reject \\( -9 \\): a length can''t be negative)", "\\( -9 \\)", "\\( 5 \\) or \\( -9 \\)", "\\( -4 \\), the sum of the roots"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Only the positive root is admissible for a length; you must reject \\( -9 \\) and say why."}}, {"title": "How do you set up and solve a cubic in context?", "html": "<p>When <strong>three</strong> quantities multiply (a volume, three consecutive numbers), you get a <strong>cubic</strong>. Find one root by inspection or the <strong>factor theorem</strong> (topic 2.2), then factor out to a quadratic and finish.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> Three consecutive positive integers have a product of 60. Find them.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Let the smallest be \\( n \\); the integers are \\( n,\\ n+1,\\ n+2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Product: \\( n(n+1)(n+2) = 60 \\), i.e. \\( n^3 + 3n^2 + 2n - 60 = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Try \\( n = 3 \\): \\( 3 \\times 4 \\times 5 = 60 \\) ✓, so \\( (n - 3) \\) is a factor.</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. Divide out: \\( (n - 3)(n^2 + 6n + 20) = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. The factor \\( n^2 + 6n + 20 \\) has discriminant \\( 36 - 80 < 0 \\) — no real roots.</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So \\( n = 3 \\), and the integers are <strong>3, 4 and 5</strong>. The quadratic factor is checked, not ignored — showing it has no valid roots is what confirms \\( n = 3 \\) is the only answer.</p>", "check": {"question": "After spotting \\( n = 3 \\) is a root of a cubic, the next step is to:", "options": ["Factor out \\( (n - 3) \\) to get a quadratic, then solve that", "Stop — one root is enough", "Square both sides", "Reject \\( n = 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Dividing out the known factor leaves a quadratic that reveals (or rules out) the remaining roots."}}, {"title": "How do you solve linear–quadratic simultaneous equations?", "html": "<p>To solve a <strong>linear</strong> equation and a <strong>non-linear</strong> one together (a line meeting a curve), use <strong>substitution</strong>: rearrange the linear equation for one variable and put it into the other.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example.</strong> Solve \\( y = x + 1 \\) and \\( x^2 + y^2 = 25 \\) simultaneously.</p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Substitute \\( y = x + 1 \\) into the second equation: \\( x^2 + (x + 1)^2 = 25 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. Expand: \\( x^2 + x^2 + 2x + 1 = 25 \\), so \\( 2x^2 + 2x - 24 = 0 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. Divide by 2 and factorise: \\( x^2 + x - 12 = 0 = (x + 4)(x - 3) \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. So \\( x = -4 \\) or \\( x = 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>5. Back-substitute into \\( y = x + 1 \\): \\( (3,\\ 4) \\) and \\( (-4,\\ -3) \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Always give the answers as <strong>pairs</strong> — each \\( x \\) with its matching \\( y \\). Check \\( 3^2 + 4^2 = 25 \\) ✓ and \\( (-4)^2 + (-3)^2 = 25 \\) ✓.</p>", "check": {"question": "To solve \\( y = 2x \\) and \\( x^2 + y^2 = 20 \\), the substitution gives:", "options": ["\\( x^2 + (2x)^2 = 20 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 2x = 20 \\)", "\\( (2x)^2 = 20 \\)", "\\( x^2 + y = 20 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Replace \\( y \\) with \\( 2x \\): \\( x^2 + (2x)^2 = 20 \\Rightarrow 5x^2 = 20 \\Rightarrow x = \\pm 2 \\)."}}, {"title": "Why must you interpret the answer and reject invalid solutions?", "html": "<p>Solving the equation is only part of the mark. Modelling questions reward <strong>interpretation</strong>: turning \\( x = 6 \\) into \"the width is 6 cm\", and discarding anything impossible.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Reject inadmissible roots.</strong> Negative lengths, negative speeds, and fractional counts of people cannot occur — say which root you keep and <em>why</em>.</li>\n              <li><strong>State a value with its units.</strong> A bare number often loses the final mark: in the 2023 boat question, \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" scored nothing extra — the examiners wanted \"speed of the current = 1 km/h\".</li>\n              <li><strong>Watch what the variable stands for.</strong> If \\( r \\) was defined as a unitless number, \"\\( r = 1 \\) km/h\" is also wrong — name the quantity: \"the speed is 1 km/h\".</li>\n              <li><strong>\"Show that\" needs the last line.</strong> If a question asks you to show an equation simplifies to a printed result, you must reach that exact result on the page.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p>Read the final sentence of the question back to yourself: does your answer actually name the thing it asked for, in the right units?</p>", "check": {"question": "A question asks for a swimmer''s speed and you find \\( v = 2 \\). The best final answer is:", "options": ["The speed is 2 m/s", "\\( v = 2 \\)", "\\( v = 2 \\) with no units", "2"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Name the quantity and give its units — a bare number or a bare variable value can lose the final mark."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Define the unknown", "definition": "State what your variable stands for, with units, before writing any equation."}, {"term": "Modelling routine", "definition": "Define, translate, solve, interpret, reject invalid solutions."}, {"term": "Inadmissible solution", "definition": "A root that cannot occur in context (e.g. a negative length); reject it."}, {"term": "Linear equation", "definition": "Unknown to the power 1; rearrange in one step per line to solve."}, {"term": "Quadratic in context", "definition": "Set up \\( ax^2 + bx + c = 0 \\), solve, and keep only physically valid roots."}, {"term": "Cubic in context", "definition": "A degree-3 equation; find one root, factor out, then solve the quadratic."}, {"term": "Simultaneous (linear + quadratic)", "definition": "Substitute the linear equation into the quadratic; solve; back-substitute."}, {"term": "Substitution method", "definition": "Replace one variable using the linear equation to get a single equation."}, {"term": "Consecutive integers", "definition": "Written \\( n,\\ n+1,\\ n+2, \\dots \\)"}, {"term": "Reject a root", "definition": "Discard a solution the context forbids, and state the reason."}, {"term": "Answer with units", "definition": "Give the final value in context with its units, e.g. ''speed = 1 km/h''."}, {"term": "Back-substitution", "definition": "After finding one variable, substitute to find the matching value of the other."}, {"term": "''Show that''", "definition": "The result is given; show every step until you reach the printed result."}, {"term": "Difference of two fractions", "definition": "\\( \\frac{a}{p} - \\frac{a}{q} = \\frac{a(q - p)}{pq} \\)."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "\"5 more than double a number \\( x \\)\" is written as:", "options": ["\\( 2x + 5 \\)", "\\( 5x + 2 \\)", "\\( 2(x + 5) \\)", "\\( 5 - 2x \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Double the number is \\( 2x \\); ''5 more than'' adds 5: \\( 2x + 5 \\)."}, {"question": "\"7 less than 4 times a number \\( n \\)\" translates to:", "options": ["\\( 4n - 7 \\)", "\\( 7 - 4n \\)", "\\( 4(n - 7) \\)", "\\( 7n - 4 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "''4 times \\( n \\)'' is \\( 4n \\); ''7 less than'' subtracts 7 from it: \\( 4n - 7 \\) (not \\( 7 - 4n \\))."}, {"question": "A taxi charges a £4 booking fee plus £3 per mile. A £22 journey is how many miles?", "options": ["6", "7", "8", "3"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 4 + 3m = 22 \\Rightarrow 3m = 18 \\Rightarrow m = 6 \\) miles."}, {"question": "A rectangle''s length is 3 cm more than its width \\( x \\), and its area is 40 cm². The correct equation is:", "options": ["\\( x^2 + 3x - 40 = 0 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 3x + 40 = 0 \\)", "\\( x^2 - 3x - 40 = 0 \\)", "\\( 3x^2 = 40 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Area \\( = x(x + 3) = 40 \\Rightarrow x^2 + 3x - 40 = 0 \\)."}, {"question": "A width satisfies \\( x^2 + 2x - 48 = 0 \\), whose roots are \\( 6 \\) and \\( -8 \\). The width is:", "options": ["6 cm", "\\( -8 \\) cm", "6 cm or \\( -8 \\) cm", "\\( -8 \\) cm, since it is further from 0"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A length cannot be negative, so reject \\( -8 \\): the width is 6 cm."}, {"question": "Two consecutive positive integers have a product of 132, so \\( n(n+1) = 132 \\) gives \\( n = 11 \\) or \\( n = -12 \\). The integers are:", "options": ["11 and 12", "\\( -12 \\) and \\( -11 \\)", "11 and \\( -12 \\)", "132 and 1"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The integers are positive, so reject \\( n = -12 \\): they are 11 and 12."}, {"question": "In the 2023 boat problem the working gives \\( r = 1 \\). The complete answer to \"find the speed of the current\" is:", "options": ["the speed of the current = 1 km/h", "\\( r = 1 \\)", "\\( r = 1 \\) km/h", "1"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Because \\( r \\) was defined as a unitless number, you must name the quantity and give units: ''speed = 1 km/h''."}, {"question": "To solve \\( y = 2x \\) and \\( x^2 + y^2 = 20 \\) by substitution you first write:", "options": ["\\( x^2 + (2x)^2 = 20 \\)", "\\( x^2 + 2x = 20 \\)", "\\( (2x)^2 = 20 \\)", "\\( x^2 + y^2 = 20 \\) with \\( y = 2 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Replace \\( y \\) by \\( 2x \\) in the quadratic: \\( x^2 + (2x)^2 = 20 \\)."}, {"question": "A straight line and a circle can meet in at most how many points (solution pairs)?", "options": ["2", "1", "0", "infinitely many"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Substituting the line into the circle gives a quadratic, which has at most two real solutions."}, {"question": "Setting up a real problem gives a quadratic with \\( b^2 - 4ac < 0 \\). This means:", "options": ["there is no real solution — re-check the model", "there are two solutions", "you should take the negative root", "the answer is 0"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A negative discriminant means no real roots, so no valid answer exists — usually a sign an equation was set up wrongly."}, {"question": "The product of three consecutive positive integers is 60. The smallest integer is:", "options": ["3", "4", "5", "2"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( n(n+1)(n+2) = 60 \\); \\( 3 \\times 4 \\times 5 = 60 \\), so the smallest is 3."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "The first step in modelling a worded problem is to define the [unknown] and state what it represents."}, {"text": "When a quadratic equation for a length gives a negative root, you must [reject] it, because a length cannot be negative."}, {"text": "To solve one linear and one quadratic equation together, use the method of [substitution]."}, {"text": "In the boat problem the two roots were 1 and \\( -16 \\); the current speed must be positive, so the answer is [1] km/h."}, {"text": "A final answer in a real context should always be stated with its [units]."}, {"text": "The phrase \"5 more than a number \\( x \\)\" translates to \\( x \\) [plus] 5."}, {"text": "Three consecutive integers can be written as \\( n \\), \\( n+1 \\) and [n+2]."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "When setting up an equation you should state what your variable represents, including its units.", "answer": true, "explain": "Defining the unknown (with units) is step 1 and prevents lost marks later."}, {"statement": "A negative solution to an equation for a length should still be given as a valid answer.", "answer": false, "explain": "A length cannot be negative, so a negative root is inadmissible and must be rejected."}, {"statement": "\"8 more than a number \\( x \\)\" is written \\( 8x \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "''8 more than'' adds 8: it is \\( x + 8 \\), not \\( 8x \\) (that would be ''8 times'')."}, {"statement": "To solve a linear equation and a quadratic equation together, you substitute the linear equation into the quadratic.", "answer": true, "explain": "Substitution reduces the pair to a single quadratic in one variable."}, {"statement": "A quadratic set up from a context always has two admissible solutions.", "answer": false, "explain": "Often one root (or both) is inadmissible — e.g. negative — and must be rejected."}, {"statement": "For the 2023 boat problem, giving the answer as \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" with no units earns full marks.", "answer": false, "explain": "The final mark needed the value in context with units: ''speed of the current = 1 km/h''."}, {"statement": "The product of three consecutive integers \\( n,\\ n+1,\\ n+2 \\) can be written \\( n^3 + 3n^2 + 2n \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "\\( n(n+1)(n+2) = n(n^2 + 3n + 2) = n^3 + 3n^2 + 2n \\)."}, {"statement": "If substituting a line into a circle gives a quadratic with no real roots, the line misses the circle.", "answer": true, "explain": "No real solutions means no intersection points — the line does not meet the circle."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "For a rectangle, \\( x^2 + 2x - 48 = 0 \\) gives \\( x = 6 \\) or \\( x = -8 \\), so the width is \\( -8 \\) cm.", "truth": "A length can never be negative. A weak answer keeps both roots; a strong answer <strong>rejects \\( x = -8 \\)</strong> and states the width is 6 cm, saying why the negative root is impossible.", "check": {"question": "Roots \\( 6 \\) and \\( -8 \\) model a width. The width is:", "options": ["6 cm (reject \\( -8 \\))", "\\( -8 \\) cm", "6 or \\( -8 \\) cm", "\\( -2 \\) cm"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Reject the negative root; the width is 6 cm."}}, {"myth": "The current speed is found by writing \\( r = 1 \\) and stopping.", "truth": "\"\\( r = 1 \\)\" is a bare number. A weak answer stops there; a strong answer gives a <strong>value with units in context</strong>: ''speed of the current = 1 km/h''. Because \\( r \\) was defined unitless, even ''\\( r = 1 \\) km/h'' is wrong.", "check": {"question": "Which is the complete answer for a current speed?", "options": ["speed = 1 km/h", "\\( r = 1 \\)", "\\( r = 1 \\) km/h", "1"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Name the quantity and give the units."}}, {"myth": "\"5 more than 3 times \\( x \\)\" is written \\( 3(x + 5) \\) or \\( 5(3x) \\).", "truth": "Translate step by step: ''3 times \\( x \\)'' is \\( 3x \\), then ''5 more than'' adds 5 to <em>that</em>: \\( 3x + 5 \\). A weak answer brackets or multiplies wrongly; a strong answer builds the expression in order.", "check": {"question": "\"5 more than 3 times \\( x \\)\" is:", "options": ["\\( 3x + 5 \\)", "\\( 3(x + 5) \\)", "\\( 5(3x) \\)", "\\( 3x - 5 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 3x \\) first, then add 5: \\( 3x + 5 \\)."}}, {"myth": "For simultaneous \\( y = x + 1 \\) and \\( x^2 + y^2 = 25 \\), the student finds \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( x = -4 \\) and stops.", "truth": "Simultaneous solutions come in <strong>pairs</strong>. A weak answer gives only the \\( x \\)-values; a strong answer back-substitutes into \\( y = x + 1 \\) to give \\( (3,\\ 4) \\) and \\( (-4,\\ -3) \\).", "check": {"question": "With \\( x = 3 \\) and \\( y = x + 1 \\), the point is:", "options": ["\\( (3,\\ 4) \\)", "\\( (3,\\ 3) \\)", "\\( (4,\\ 3) \\)", "\\( (3,\\ 0) \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( y = 3 + 1 = 4 \\), so the pair is \\( (3,\\ 4) \\)."}}, {"myth": "\"Show that the equation simplifies to \\( r^2 + 15r - 16 = 0 \\)\" is answered by solving it to get \\( r = 1 \\).", "truth": "A ''show that'' asks you to <strong>reach the printed result</strong>, not to solve it. A weak answer jumps to the roots; a strong answer clears the fractions and rearranges line by line until \\( r^2 + 15r - 16 = 0 \\) appears.", "check": {"question": "A ''show that'' question wants you to:", "options": ["Derive the given result step by step", "Solve for the unknown", "Give a decimal answer", "Draw the graph"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The result is given; you must show the working that leads to it."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "The modelling routine (0 → full marks)", "html": "<p><strong>0 marks:</strong> jumping straight to numbers with no defined variable and no units.</p><p><strong>Partial:</strong> a correct equation solved to a bare number, e.g. \"\\( x = 6 \\)\", with no context.</p><p><strong>Full marks:</strong> \"Let \\( x \\) be the width in cm\" → \\( x(x+2) = 48 \\) → \\( x = 6 \\) (reject \\( -8 \\)) → \"the width is 6 cm, the length 8 cm\". Define, translate, solve, interpret.</p>", "check": {"question": "What lifts a partial answer to full marks in a modelling question?", "options": ["Defining the variable and interpreting the answer in context with units", "Working faster", "Giving a decimal", "Using a graph"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The interpretation and definition steps carry marks beyond just solving."}}, {"title": "Reject the impossible root", "html": "<p>Every quadratic or cubic from a context can throw up a root that cannot happen — a negative length, a negative speed, a fractional person. Write the rejected root down and say <strong>why</strong>: \"reject \\( x = -8 \\) as a width cannot be negative.\" Silently dropping it can still lose the reasoning mark.</p>", "check": {"question": "When you reject a root you should:", "options": ["State which root and why it is impossible", "Erase it with no comment", "Keep both roots anyway", "Round it to zero"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Examiners credit the explicit rejection with a reason."}}, {"title": "Answer with a value AND units", "html": "<p>The final mark in a modelling question is often for the <strong>form of the answer</strong>. In 2023''s boat question, \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" and even \"\\( r = 1 \\) km/h\" were marked wrong because \\( r \\) was a unitless variable — the answer needed was \"the speed of the current is 1 km/h\". Always name the quantity the question asked for and attach its units.</p>", "check": {"question": "Why did \"\\( r = 1 \\)\" lose the final mark in the 2023 boat question?", "options": ["It gave a bare value, not the speed with units in context", "The arithmetic was wrong", "\\( r = 1 \\) is not a root", "It used the wrong formula"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The question asked for the speed of the current, which must be stated as a value with units."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "<p>Show that the time it takes me to drive up the river from \\( A \\) to \\( B \\) is \\( \\dfrac{9}{4 - r} \\) hours.</p>", "marks": 2, "hint": "Use time = distance ÷ speed. Against the current the boat''s effective speed is \\( 4 - r \\).", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 2 marks (AO2)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — sight of the relationship \\( \\text{time} = \\dfrac{\\text{distance}}{\\text{speed}} \\) (must see evidence of the relationship).</li>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — reasoning that the upstream speed is \\( 4 - r \\), giving \\( \\dfrac{9}{4 - r} \\) (AG).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>One mark is for the distance–speed–time relationship, one for explaining the denominator \\( 4 - r \\). The printed result must be reached.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Candidates were able to provide a version of distance = speed × time, although some resorted to quoting one or other suvat equations. Few were able to explain the denominator satisfactorily.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>I also drive at maximum speed on my return journey down the river from \\( B \\) to \\( A \\).</p>\n            <p>Write down, in terms of \\( r \\), the time it takes me to drive down the river from \\( B \\) to \\( A \\).</p>", "marks": 1, "hint": "Going downstream, the current adds to the boat''s speed.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 1 mark (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — \\( \\dfrac{9}{4 + r} \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>Downstream the effective speed is \\( 4 + r \\), so the time is \\( \\dfrac{9}{4 + r} \\).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>There was little difficulty in writing down the correct fraction.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>Given that the difference between the time to drive up the river (a) and the time to drive down the river (b) is 1.2 hours, form an equation in \\( r \\) and show that it simplifies to \\( r^2 + 15r - 16 = 0 \\).</p>", "marks": 4, "hint": "Set (up-time) − (down-time) = 1.2, then multiply through by \\( (4 - r)(4 + r) \\) to clear the fractions.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 4 marks (AO3)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — sight of the difference of their two times, e.g. \\( \\dfrac{9}{4 - r} - \\dfrac{9}{4 + r} = 1.2 \\) (accept fractions either way round).</li>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — eliminate the fractions from the equation, leaving \\( r \\) only.</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — correct (unsimplified) equation, e.g. \\( 18r = 1.2(16 - r^2) \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — reaches the given \\( r^2 + 15r - 16 = 0 \\) (AG www).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>Mark for the difference of times, for clearing fractions, for a correct unsimplified equation, and for the printed result with no wrong working.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Most identified the need to subtract the two fractions, although there were many who gave the subtraction the wrong way round. To achieve the given answer the difference in times had to be the correct way round. Once the equation with the fractions was established, the elimination of the fractions was generally well attempted.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}, {"question": "<p>Hence find the speed of the current down the river.</p>", "marks": 3, "hint": "Solve \\( r^2 + 15r - 16 = 0 \\) by factorising, then reject the impossible root and give a value with units.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 3 marks (AO3)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>M1</strong> — factorisation by sight of \\( (r - 1)(r + 16) = 0 \\) (soi); if by formula, correct substitutions into the correct formula, allowing one sign error.</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — \\( r = 1 \\) (possibly also stating \\( r = -16 \\)).</li>\n              <li><strong>A1</strong> — speed of the current is 1 km h⁻¹ (the value in context, with units).</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>Mark for a valid solution method, for the value \\( r = 1 \\), and for the answer stated as a speed with units in context.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>The equation was generally correctly solved. However, many lost the last mark for failing to give the units for the speed of the current, either correctly or at all. The question asked for the speed of the current. \\( r = 1 \\) was therefore not the complete answer. \\( r = 1 \\) km/hr was also incorrect as \\( r \\) is a variable with no units. The complete answer of ''speed = 1 km/hr'' was not always seen.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
('additional-maths', '2-4-sequences-and-recurrence-relationships', '2.4 Sequences and Recurrence Relationships', '{"learn": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "What is a recurrence relationship?", "html": "<p>A <strong>recurrence relationship</strong> (or recurrence relation) is a rule that gives each term of a sequence from one or more <em>earlier</em> terms. It is a <strong>term-to-term</strong> rule, not a position-to-term formula.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li>The <strong>subscript</strong> tells you the position: \\( x_n \\) is the \\( n\\)th term, \\( x_{n+1} \\) is the term straight after it, and \\( x_{n+2} \\) is the one after that.</li>\n              <li>A rule such as \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\) reads \"the next term equals this term plus 3\".</li>\n              <li>You cannot generate the sequence from the rule alone — you also need a <strong>starting value</strong> (the first term). A rule that reaches back two terms, like \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\), needs <strong>two</strong> starting values.</li>\n              <li>The phrase \"<em>for all positive integers \\( n \\)</em>\" simply means the rule applies right from the start of the sequence.</li>\n            </ul>", "check": {"question": "In \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 5 \\), what does \\( x_{n+1} \\) represent?", "options": ["The term immediately after \\( x_n \\)", "The term immediately before \\( x_n \\)", "\\( 5 \\) times \\( x_n \\)", "The starting value of the sequence"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The subscript \\( n+1 \\) is one position further on than \\( n \\), so \\( x_{n+1} \\) is the next term after \\( x_n \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you generate an arithmetic (linear) sequence?", "html": "<p>A first-order recurrence of the form \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) <strong>adds</strong> the same fixed amount \\( a \\) to get each new term. This produces an <strong>arithmetic</strong> sequence — a constant step up (or, if \\( a \\) is negative, down).</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — generate the first four terms of \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 4 \\) with \\( x_1 = 3 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Start: \\( x_1 = 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( x_2 = x_1 + 4 = 3 + 4 = 7 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( x_3 = x_2 + 4 = 7 + 4 = 11 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. \\( x_4 = x_3 + 4 = 11 + 4 = 15 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the sequence begins \\( 3,\\ 7,\\ 11,\\ 15,\\ \\dots \\) — a fixed step of \\( +4 \\), the <strong>common difference</strong>.</p>", "check": {"question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 6 \\) with \\( x_1 = 5 \\), find \\( x_3 \\).", "options": ["\\( 17 \\)", "\\( 11 \\)", "\\( 23 \\)", "\\( 30 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 5 + 6 = 11 \\), then \\( x_3 = 11 + 6 = 17 \\). (\\( 11 \\) is only \\( x_2 \\); \\( 23 \\) is \\( x_4 \\).)"}}, {"title": "How do you generate a geometric sequence?", "html": "<p>A first-order recurrence of the form \\( x_{n+1} = a\\,x_n \\) <strong>multiplies</strong> by the same fixed factor \\( a \\) each time. This produces a <strong>geometric</strong> sequence, with a constant <strong>common ratio</strong> \\( a \\).</p>\n            <p><strong>Watch the difference:</strong> \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) <em>adds</em> \\( a \\); \\( x_{n+1} = a\\,x_n \\) <em>multiplies</em> by \\( a \\). Mixing these up is the most common slip in this topic.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — generate the first four terms of \\( x_{n+1} = 3x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Start: \\( x_1 = 2 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( x_2 = 3 \\times 2 = 6 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( x_3 = 3 \\times 6 = 18 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. \\( x_4 = 3 \\times 18 = 54 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the sequence is \\( 2,\\ 6,\\ 18,\\ 54,\\ \\dots \\) — each term \\( 3 \\) times the last.</p>", "check": {"question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 2x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 5 \\), find \\( x_4 \\).", "options": ["\\( 40 \\)", "\\( 20 \\)", "\\( 80 \\)", "\\( 11 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 10,\\ x_3 = 20,\\ x_4 = 40 \\). (\\( 20 \\) is \\( x_3 \\); \\( 11 \\) comes from adding instead of multiplying.)"}}, {"title": "How do you work with a second-order recurrence?", "html": "<p>A <strong>second-order</strong> recurrence uses the <strong>two</strong> previous terms, so it needs <strong>two</strong> starting values. The most famous example is the <strong>Fibonacci-style</strong> rule \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\): each term is the sum of the two before it.</p>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — generate the first five terms of \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\) and \\( x_2 = 3 \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. Given: \\( x_1 = 2,\\ x_2 = 3 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. \\( x_3 = x_2 + x_1 = 3 + 2 = 5 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. \\( x_4 = x_3 + x_2 = 5 + 3 = 8 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. \\( x_5 = x_4 + x_3 = 8 + 5 = 13 \\).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>So the first five terms are \\( 2,\\ 3,\\ 5,\\ 8,\\ 13 \\). Write each line out: examiners reward every correct term, and a single arithmetic slip then costs only one mark.</p>", "check": {"question": "For \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 1 \\) and \\( x_2 = 4 \\), find \\( x_4 \\).", "options": ["\\( 9 \\)", "\\( 5 \\)", "\\( 14 \\)", "\\( 8 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_3 = 4 + 1 = 5 \\), then \\( x_4 = x_3 + x_2 = 5 + 4 = 9 \\)."}}, {"title": "How do you describe a sequence by a recurrence?", "html": "<p>Sometimes you are given a sequence and asked for the recurrence that <strong>describes</strong> it. Look for the pattern, then state the rule <em>and</em> the starting value(s).</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Constant difference</strong> between terms → \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + d \\) (arithmetic).</li>\n              <li><strong>Constant ratio</strong> between terms → \\( x_{n+1} = r\\,x_n \\) (geometric).</li>\n              <li>Each term the <strong>sum of the two before</strong> → \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\).</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — describe \\( 5,\\ 8,\\ 11,\\ 14,\\ \\dots \\):</strong> the difference is a constant \\( +3 \\), so \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\) with \\( x_1 = 5 \\). A rule without its starting value does not fully define the sequence, so always give both.</p>", "check": {"question": "Which recurrence describes the sequence \\( 4,\\ 12,\\ 36,\\ 108,\\ \\dots \\)?", "options": ["\\( x_{n+1} = 3x_n,\\ x_1 = 4 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 8,\\ x_1 = 4 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\)", "\\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Each term is \\( 3 \\) times the last (\\( 12 = 3 \\times 4 \\), \\( 36 = 3 \\times 12 \\)), so it is geometric with ratio \\( 3 \\) and \\( x_1 = 4 \\)."}}, {"title": "How is recurrence used to model money and populations?", "html": "<p>Recurrence relationships model any quantity that changes by the <strong>same factor</strong> each period — the classic case is <strong>compound interest</strong>.</p>\n            <ul>\n              <li><strong>Growth of \\( r\\% \\) per period</strong> → multiply by \\( \\left(1 + \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\). So \\( 3\\% \\) interest gives \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03\\,x_n \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Depreciation / decay of \\( r\\% \\)</strong> → multiply by \\( \\left(1 - \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\). So losing \\( 15\\% \\) a year gives \\( x_{n+1} = 0.85\\,x_n \\).</li>\n              <li><strong>Regular top-up savings</strong> combine both: e.g. \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03\\,x_n + 50 \\) grows the balance by \\( 3\\% \\) and then adds a \\( £50 \\) deposit.</li>\n            </ul>\n            <p><strong>Worked example — £500 invested at \\( 3\\% \\) per year, \\( x_1 = 500 \\), \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03\\,x_n \\):</strong></p>\n            <table class=\"worked\">\n              <tr><td>1. \\( x_1 = 500 \\) (the amount invested).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>2. After 1 year: \\( x_2 = 1.03 \\times 500 = 515 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>3. After 2 years: \\( x_3 = 1.03 \\times 515 = 530.45 \\).</td></tr>\n              <tr><td>4. After 3 years: \\( x_4 = 1.03 \\times 530.45 = 546.36 \\) (to the nearest penny).</td></tr>\n            </table>\n            <p>Interest is earned on the interest, so the balance grows a little faster each year.</p>", "check": {"question": "A car worth \\( £8000 \\) depreciates by \\( 20\\% \\) each year. Which recurrence models its value?", "options": ["\\( x_{n+1} = 0.8x_n \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = 1.2x_n \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n - 20 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = 0.2x_n \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Losing \\( 20\\% \\) leaves \\( 80\\% \\), so multiply by \\( 1 - 0.20 = 0.8 \\)."}}]}, "terms": {"enabled": true, "pairs": [{"term": "Recurrence relationship", "definition": "A rule giving each term of a sequence from one or more earlier terms."}, {"term": "\\( x_n \\)", "definition": "The \\( n\\)th term of a sequence."}, {"term": "\\( x_{n+1} \\)", "definition": "The term immediately after \\( x_n \\)."}, {"term": "\\( x_{n+2} \\)", "definition": "The term two places after \\( x_n \\)."}, {"term": "Starting value", "definition": "The first term(s) you must be given to begin a recurrence."}, {"term": "First-order recurrence", "definition": "A rule using only the previous term, e.g. \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\)."}, {"term": "Second-order recurrence", "definition": "A rule using the two previous terms, e.g. \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\)."}, {"term": "Arithmetic recurrence", "definition": "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\): adds a fixed amount each term."}, {"term": "Geometric recurrence", "definition": "\\( x_{n+1} = a x_n \\): multiplies by a fixed factor each term."}, {"term": "Fibonacci sequence", "definition": "\\( 1,\\ 1,\\ 2,\\ 3,\\ 5,\\ 8,\\ \\dots \\); each term is the sum of the two before it."}, {"term": "Compound interest multiplier", "definition": "\\( 1 + \\frac{r}{100} \\); e.g. 3% gives \\( 1.03 \\)."}, {"term": "Depreciation multiplier", "definition": "\\( 1 - \\frac{r}{100} \\); e.g. losing 15% gives \\( 0.85 \\)."}, {"term": "Common difference", "definition": "The constant amount added each term in an arithmetic sequence."}, {"term": "Common ratio", "definition": "The constant factor multiplied each term in a geometric sequence."}, {"term": "''Determine''", "definition": "Command word: give the value supported by working."}]}, "mcq": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 7 \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\), find \\( x_4 \\).", "options": ["\\( 23 \\)", "\\( 16 \\)", "\\( 30 \\)", "\\( 9 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 9,\\ x_3 = 16,\\ x_4 = 23 \\). (\\( 16 \\) is \\( x_3 \\); \\( 30 \\) is \\( x_5 \\).)"}, {"question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 4x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 3 \\), find \\( x_3 \\).", "options": ["\\( 48 \\)", "\\( 12 \\)", "\\( 192 \\)", "\\( 11 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 4 \\times 3 = 12,\\ x_3 = 4 \\times 12 = 48 \\). (\\( 12 \\) is \\( x_2 \\); \\( 192 \\) is \\( x_4 \\).)"}, {"question": "For \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 3 \\) and \\( x_2 = 5 \\), find \\( x_5 \\).", "options": ["\\( 21 \\)", "\\( 13 \\)", "\\( 34 \\)", "\\( 18 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_3 = 8,\\ x_4 = 13,\\ x_5 = 21 \\). (\\( 13 \\) is \\( x_4 \\); \\( 34 \\) is \\( x_6 \\).)"}, {"question": "A student is told \\( x_{n+1} = 5x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\) and writes \\( x_2 = 7 \\). What went wrong?", "options": ["They added 5 instead of multiplying by 5 — it should be \\( x_2 = 10 \\)", "Nothing — \\( x_2 = 7 \\) is correct", "They should get \\( x_2 = 25 \\)", "They used the wrong starting value"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_{n+1} = 5x_n \\) multiplies: \\( x_2 = 5 \\times 2 = 10 \\). Writing \\( 2 + 5 = 7 \\) confuses it with \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 5 \\)."}, {"question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\) with \\( x_1 = 4 \\), a student says the 3rd term is 13. What is the actual 3rd term?", "options": ["\\( 10 \\)", "\\( 13 \\)", "\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 16 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_1 = 4,\\ x_2 = 7,\\ x_3 = 10 \\). The value \\( 13 \\) is \\( x_4 \\) — an off-by-one counting error."}, {"question": "Which recurrence generates the sequence \\( 2,\\ 10,\\ 50,\\ 250,\\ \\dots \\)?", "options": ["\\( x_{n+1} = 5x_n,\\ x_1 = 2 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 8 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 40 \\)", "\\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Each term is \\( 5 \\) times the last (\\( 10 = 5 \\times 2 \\)), so it is geometric with ratio \\( 5 \\) and \\( x_1 = 2 \\)."}, {"question": "£2000 is invested at \\( 4\\% \\) compound interest per year. Which recurrence models the balance?", "options": ["\\( x_{n+1} = 1.04x_n \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 4 \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = 0.04x_n \\)", "\\( x_{n+1} = 1.4x_n \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Growth of \\( 4\\% \\) multiplies by \\( 1 + 0.04 = 1.04 \\). Adding \\( 4 \\) would be simple interest of only £4."}, {"question": "A machine loses \\( 10\\% \\) of its value each year. In \\( x_{n+1} = k\\,x_n \\), what is \\( k \\)?", "options": ["\\( 0.9 \\)", "\\( 1.1 \\)", "\\( 0.1 \\)", "\\( 0.09 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Losing \\( 10\\% \\) leaves \\( 90\\% \\), so \\( k = 1 - 0.10 = 0.9 \\)."}, {"question": "To generate a sequence from \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\), what must you be given?", "options": ["Two starting values", "One starting value", "No starting values", "The 100th term"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The rule reaches back two terms, so you need the first two terms before you can start."}, {"question": "£400 grows at \\( 5\\% \\) per year: \\( x_{n+1} = 1.05x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 400 \\). Find \\( x_3 \\).", "options": ["\\( £441.00 \\)", "\\( £420.00 \\)", "\\( £463.05 \\)", "\\( £440.00 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 1.05 \\times 400 = 420 \\), then \\( x_3 = 1.05 \\times 420 = 441 \\). (\\( 420 \\) is \\( x_2 \\); \\( 463.05 \\) is \\( x_4 \\).)"}, {"question": "For \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + 2x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\) and \\( x_2 = 1 \\), find \\( x_4 \\).", "options": ["\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 5 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)", "\\( 11 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_3 = x_2 + 2x_1 = 1 + 4 = 5 \\), then \\( x_4 = x_3 + 2x_2 = 5 + 2 = 7 \\)."}]}, "fib": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"text": "A rule that gives each term of a sequence from earlier terms is called a [recurrence] relationship."}, {"text": "As well as the rule, you need a [starting] value before you can generate the sequence."}, {"text": "In \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) the fixed number \\( a \\) is [added] to each term, giving an arithmetic sequence."}, {"text": "In \\( x_{n+1} = a x_n \\) each term is [multiplied] by \\( a \\), giving a geometric sequence."}, {"text": "A second-order rule such as \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) needs [two] starting values."}, {"text": "Compound interest of 3% per year gives \\( x_{n+1} = k x_n \\) where the multiplier \\( k \\) is [1.03]."}, {"text": "An asset that loses 15% of its value each year has multiplier [0.85]."}, {"text": "For \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 4 \\) with \\( x_1 = 3 \\), the second term is [7] and the third term is [11]."}]}, "tf": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"statement": "A recurrence relationship needs at least one starting value to generate the sequence.", "answer": true, "explain": "The rule only tells you how to get from known terms to the next, so you must be given a first term (or two, for a second-order rule) to begin."}, {"statement": "\\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) describes a sequence that changes by a fixed amount each term.", "answer": true, "explain": "Adding the same \\( a \\) every step gives a constant common difference — an arithmetic sequence."}, {"statement": "\\( x_{n+1} = a x_n \\) and \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + a \\) generate the same sequence.", "answer": false, "explain": "The first multiplies by \\( a \\) (geometric), the second adds \\( a \\) (arithmetic) — quite different sequences."}, {"statement": "A second-order recurrence such as \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) can be started from a single value.", "answer": false, "explain": "It uses the two previous terms, so it needs two starting values."}, {"statement": "£1000 at 3% compound interest per year is modelled by \\( x_{n+1} = 1.03 x_n \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "Growth of 3% multiplies the balance by \\( 1 + 0.03 = 1.03 \\) each year."}, {"statement": "In the sequence \\( 5,\\ 8,\\ 11,\\ 14,\\ \\dots \\) the recurrence is \\( x_{n+1} = x_n + 3 \\).", "answer": true, "explain": "The constant difference is \\( +3 \\), so each term is the previous term plus 3 (with \\( x_1 = 5 \\))."}, {"statement": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 2x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 3 \\), the term \\( x_3 \\) equals 12.", "answer": true, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 6 \\) and \\( x_3 = 2 \\times 6 = 12 \\)."}, {"statement": "An asset that depreciates by 15% each year is modelled by \\( x_{n+1} = 1.15 x_n \\).", "answer": false, "explain": "Depreciation of 15% leaves 85%, so the multiplier is \\( 0.85 \\), not \\( 1.15 \\)."}]}, "misc": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"myth": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 5x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\), writing \\( x_2 = 2 + 5 = 7 \\).", "truth": "The rule multiplies, it does not add. A weak answer treats \\( 5x_n \\) as \\( x_n + 5 \\); a strong answer writes \\( x_2 = 5 \\times 2 = 10 \\).", "check": {"question": "For \\( x_{n+1} = 5x_n \\) with \\( x_1 = 2 \\), what is \\( x_2 \\)?", "options": ["\\( 10 \\)", "\\( 7 \\)", "\\( 25 \\)", "\\( 5 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( x_2 = 5 \\times 2 = 10 \\)."}}, {"myth": "Trying to generate \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) from a single starting value.", "truth": "A second-order rule needs two terms to start. A weak answer stalls with only \\( x_1 \\); a strong answer uses both \\( x_1 \\) and \\( x_2 \\), then builds \\( x_3 = x_2 + x_1 \\).", "check": {"question": "How many starting values does \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + x_n \\) need?", "options": ["Two", "One", "None", "Three"], "answer": 0, "explain": "It reaches back two terms, so it needs the first two terms."}}, {"myth": "Doing the whole iteration on the calculator and writing down only the final answer.", "truth": "Examiners award a mark for each correct term, so unshown working can lose marks after a slip. A weak answer shows nothing; a strong answer sets each line out formally: \\( x_3 = \\dots,\\ x_4 = \\dots,\\ x_5 = \\dots \\). This also guards against a transcription error when copying from the calculator.", "check": {"question": "Why set out each term on its own line?", "options": ["Each correct term earns its own mark and it prevents copying slips", "It uses more paper", "It is required by law", "To make the answer look longer"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Every term is worth a mark, and formal working avoids calculator transcription errors."}}, {"myth": "Not recognising the phrase ''recurrence relationship'' and leaving the question blank.", "truth": "''Recurrence relationship'' just means a term-to-term rule — a way of getting the next term from earlier ones. A weak answer gives up on the wording; a strong answer reads the rule and simply substitutes the given values.", "check": {"question": "What does ''recurrence relationship'' mean?", "options": ["A rule giving each term from earlier terms", "The sum of all the terms", "The 100th term of the sequence", "A type of graph"], "answer": 0, "explain": "It is a term-to-term rule — nothing more exotic than substituting into the given formula."}}, {"myth": "Modelling 3% compound interest with the multiplier \\( 0.03 \\) or \\( 1.3 \\).", "truth": "A percentage increase adds to 1, and 3% is \\( 0.03 \\), not \\( 0.3 \\). A weak answer uses \\( 0.03 \\) or \\( 1.3 \\); a strong answer uses \\( 1 + 0.03 = 1.03 \\).", "check": {"question": "The multiplier for a 3% yearly increase is:", "options": ["\\( 1.03 \\)", "\\( 0.03 \\)", "\\( 1.3 \\)", "\\( 3 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "\\( 1 + \\frac{3}{100} = 1.03 \\)."}}]}, "tips": {"enabled": true, "items": [{"title": "Show every term (method marks)", "html": "<p>On a \"[3]\" recurrence question, each correct term earns <strong>its own mark</strong>. For \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + 2x_n \\), write \\( x_3 \\), \\( x_4 \\) and \\( x_5 \\) on separate lines — a slip then costs one mark, not all three. Doing it all silently on the calculator risks losing the lot to one arithmetic error.</p>", "check": {"question": "Why write each term of a recurrence on its own line?", "options": ["Each correct term earns a separate mark", "It is not necessary", "To slow yourself down", "To fill the answer space"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Marks are awarded term by term, so visible correct terms protect your score."}}, {"title": "''Determine'' means value plus working", "html": "<p>The command word <strong>\"Determine\"</strong> asks for the value <em>supported by working</em> — you must show how you reached it, not just state the final number. For \\( x_5 \\), show the terms you built on the way (\\( x_3 \\), \\( x_4 \\)) so the method is clear.</p>", "check": {"question": "What does ''Determine the value of \\( x_5 \\)'' require?", "options": ["The value with working shown", "Only the final number", "A graph of the sequence", "A decimal approximation"], "answer": 0, "explain": "''Determine'' expects justification — the value backed by visible working."}}, {"title": "Turn a percentage into a multiplier", "html": "<p>For modelling questions, convert the rate to a multiplier: a rise of \\( r\\% \\) gives \\( \\left(1 + \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\); a fall of \\( r\\% \\) gives \\( \\left(1 - \\frac{r}{100}\\right) \\). So \\( 3\\% \\) growth is \\( 1.03 \\) and \\( 15\\% \\) depreciation is \\( 0.85 \\). Then the model is simply \\( x_{n+1} = (\\text{multiplier})\\,x_n \\).</p>", "check": {"question": "The multiplier for a 7% yearly decrease is:", "options": ["\\( 0.93 \\)", "\\( 1.07 \\)", "\\( 0.07 \\)", "\\( 0.7 \\)"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A fall of 7% leaves 93%, so multiply by \\( 1 - 0.07 = 0.93 \\)."}}]}, "exam": {"enabled": true, "questions": [{"question": "<p>You are given the recurrence relationship \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + 2x_n \\) for all positive integers \\( n \\) where \\( x_1 = 1 \\) and \\( x_2 = 1 \\).</p><p>Determine the value of \\( x_5 \\).</p>", "marks": 3, "hint": "Use the two previous terms each time. Work up from \\( x_3 \\) to \\( x_5 \\), writing each line out.", "markScheme": "<div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Mark Scheme — 3 marks (AO1)</h5><ul>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — \\( x_3 = 3 \\) www.</li>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — \\( x_4 = 5 \\) www.</li>\n              <li><strong>B1</strong> — \\( x_5 = 11 \\) www.</li>\n              <li><strong>SC B2</strong> — for the answer \\( 11 \\) www with no supporting working.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>How the marks are given</h5><ul>\n              <li>One mark for each correct new term reached using the rule \\( x_{n+2} = x_{n+1} + 2x_n \\): \\( x_3 = x_2 + 2x_1 = 1 + 2 = 3 \\), \\( x_4 = x_3 + 2x_2 = 3 + 2 = 5 \\), \\( x_5 = x_4 + 2x_3 = 5 + 6 = 11 \\).</li>\n              <li>\"www\" = with working shown. A fully correct answer of \\( 11 \\) with no working scores the special case SC B2.</li>\n            </ul></div>\n            <div class=\"marks-section\"><h5>Examiner''s Comments</h5><ul>\n              <li>Most candidates were familiar with the concept of a recurrence relationship and were able to score all 3 marks. Some lost marks through arithmetic slips or doing all the work on the calculator and hence making errors in the calculation.</li>\n              <li>Candidates should set their working out in a formal way even for relatively straightforward questions. Some less successful candidates were unfamiliar with the term \"recurrence relationship\", or with the idea of a rule that calculates a term from the two previous terms, and so could not score.</li>\n            </ul></div>"}]}}'::jsonb),
